<HEADLINE> China Records High Growth Rate Accompanied by Low Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The State Statistics Bureau
announced today that China's economy has entered a phase of "high
growth and low inflation."
</P>
<P>
The bureau's Annual Report on 1997 National Economic and Social
Development released today shows that China recorded an annual
growth rate of 8.8 percent in 1997, with the increase rate for
retail prices of commodities falling by 5.3 percentage points and
the rate of consumer prices for household goods dropping by 5.5
percentage points on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The report revealed that the 1997 gross domestic product (GDP)
reached 7,477.2 billion yuan (900.9 billion US dollars). Retail
prices for commodities rose by 0.8 percent on 1996 and consumer
prices for household goods rose by 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Liu Hong, director of the State
Statistics Bureau, said the fact that China followed the principle
of "seeking development through stability" for economic
development and strengthened macro-regulatory policies in 1997
helped to maintain the good momentum of the economy. He noted that
the economy has continued to grow at a moderately high rate
accompanied by low inflation pressures since the "soft landing" in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that macro-regulation, consecutive
bumper harvests, the emergence of a buyer's market and the
strengthened role of market mechanisms were the main factors
helping to curb price increases.
</P>
<P>
The report also pointed to a number of problems existing in the
course of economic and social development, including the
irrational industrial structure, weak agriculture sector and the
low overall quality and efficiency of the national economy; poor
economic efficiency resulting from the production and management
difficulties of state-owned enterprises; rising reemployment
pressure resulting from the increased number of laid-off workers;
incomplete financial supervision system; disorder in certain
aspects of the banking sector; and mounting difficulties faced by
low-income families.
</P>
<P>
Statistics revealed that 675 state enterprises in 111 cities
either declared bankruptcy or were closed, with an additional
1,022 enterprises subject to mergers. Excessive stockpiles of
finished products continued to be a prominent problem affecting
enterprises. The year ended with industrial enterprises holding
stockpiles of finished products valued at 592.1 billion yuan, up
by 11.7 percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The problem of loss-making enterprises remained grave at the
end of the year, according to the report. Total losses suffered by
industrial enterprises with independent accounting hit 134.1
billion yuan, up 11.1 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that 432 major state-owned wholesale and
retail enterprises recorded annual net sales of 235 billion yuan
in 1997. Nonetheless their total profits dropped by 5.9 percent on
1996 levels to end at 4.4 billion yuan, a fact which fully
indicated the failure to improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the registered unemployment rate in
urban areas stood at 3.1 percent at the end of 1997, up 0.1
percentage points on the previous year. A total of 4.8 million
redundant workers found new jobs through various channels. Some
1.92 million people in 330 cities across the nation received
relief funds to ensure the minimum standard of living during the
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
