<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Tomb Chambers Discovered in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- American archaeologists have
discovered 46 more chambers in an ancient tomb already under
excavation in Luxor, Upper Egypt, the Middle East News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ancient rooms, which lie in six corridors measuring 48
meters long each, belong to the tombs of sons of King Ramses II
and are supposedly served as storing burial furnishings.
</P>
<P>
This discovery has brought the number of newly uncovered
chambers in the tomb to 108 since it was first discovered at the
end of the 19th century as a small two-room tomb in Luxor, about 600
kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Egyptian antiquities department Mohamed el-Sagheer
described the tomb as a "memorable" archaeological find.
</P>
<P>
"It boasts a unique architectural design and is the largest
tomb to be uncovered until now in the Valley of the Kings," said
the Egyptian official.
</P>
<P>
He voiced belief that continued excavations and digging in the
Ramses II tomb will unveil exciting scientific and archaeological
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
Ramses II was the third king of the 19th dynasty of Egypt whose
reign (1304-1237 B.C.) was the second longest in Egyptian
history. In addition to his military exploits, he was known for his
extensive building programs and the many colossal statues of him
found all over Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Ramses II, died at the age of 95, had about 52 sons and 48
daughters from eight wives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
