<HEADLINE> Russian Lower House Adopts 1998 Draft Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma, or the
lower house of parliament, passed the 1998 draft budget in its
fourth reading on Wednesday with a vote of 252 to 129.
</P>
<P>
The budget projects that the government this year would spend
499.9 billion redenominated rubles (about 83.3 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On the revenue side, the state coffers are expected to receive
367.5 billion rubles (61.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
An Itar-Tass news agency report said the projections are based
on a gross domestic product (GDP) target of 284 billion rubles (44
billion dollars) and an annual inflation of 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Budget deficit is set at a maximum 132.3 billion rubles (22
billion dollars), or 4.7 percent of the country's GDP.
</P>
<P>
At the Duma, where the budget bill was introduced on August 25,
1997, deputies from all groups cast their vote on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our Home is Russia" and the Liberal Democratic Party of
Russian backed the bill almost unanimously. Some 40 percent of the
Communist Party deputies also showed support.
</P>
<P>
The Yabloko faction unanimously voted against the budget.
</P>
<P>
The draft will reach the floor of the the Federation Council,
or the upper house of parliament, in the next few days and then
pass over to President Boris Yeltsin for signing into law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
