<HEADLINE> China Become World's Tenth Largest Trading Nation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China was the world's tenth
largest trading nation in 1997, with the year's foreign trade
volume hitting 325.1 billion US dollars, according to the annual
report released by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
China ranked as the world's 11th largest trade power for five
years running prior to 1997.
</P>
<P>
Imports for the year stood at 142.4 billion US dollar, with
exports totalling 182.7 billion US dollars. China ranked as the
world's 12th largest importer and tenth largest exporter.
</P>
<P>
The nation's foreign exchange reserves grew to 143 billion US
dollars at the end of the year. China ranked second in the world
in terms of total foreign exchange reserves. The 1997 figure
represented a substantial rise on 1996 foreign exchange reserves
of 105 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
