<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Records Low increase Rates for Market Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China witnessed low increases and
slight fluctuations in market prices during 1997, according to a
report released by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Retail prices for commodities grew by 0.8 percent on the
previous year, with consumer prices rising by 2.8 percent. Said
figures represented respective 5.3 and 5.5 percentage points
declines in price increase rate compared to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices in urban areas increased 3.1 percent, with the
actual increase rate dropping by 5.7 percentage points on
1996. Consumer prices in rural areas rose 2.5 percent, with the
actual increase rate falling by 5.4 percentage points on the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Prices for means of agricultural production dropped
0.5 percent, with ex-factory prices for industrial products
falling by 0.3 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes the gratifying situation to correct
macro-readjustments and the successive bumper harvests, as well as
the formation of a buyer's market, the intensification of market
mechanism, and tightened effort to rein in inflation.
</P>
<P>
Economists noted that continuing low increase rates for market
prices will pave the way for China's rapid and sound economic
development accompanied by high growth and low inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
