<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blairs Says Real Progress Must be Made at N.Irish Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Wednesday Northern Ireland peace talks had to make real
progress so hopes for the future drove out demons of the past.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the parliament, Blair said the latest killings in
Northern Ireland was a "dreadful atrocity" but said prospects for
peace remained good.
</P>
<P>
A Protestant and a Roman Catholic, lifelong friends, were shot
dead by two masked gunmen as they had a drink at a pub in
Poyntzpass village south of Belfast Tuesday night. Two other
people were injured in the shooting. Police said three people in
connection with the murders had been arrested for questioning.
</P>
<P>
The friendship between two victims of the pub shooting
represented the way ahead while the gunmen represented the past,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"There will always be extremists who seek to disrupt a process
such as the peace process in Northern Ireland, and they must not
be allowed to get their way."
</P>
<P>
"It remains the case that on any objective analysis the
prospects for a settlement are good, and we have to work towards
that with renewed vigour and determination. Democracy must defeat
evil," the prime minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted the Northern Ireland talks precess would not be
derailed by the violent acts in the recent months.
</P>
<P>
The incident was the latest in a series of sectarian attacks in
which about 20 people have been killed since last Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
