<HEADLINE> Britain Sees Record Number of Foreign Tourists in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain received a record number of
25.96 million foreign tourists in 1997, three percent up over
1996, Tourism Minister Tom Clarke said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign visitors had spent a total of 12.65 billion pounds
(20.9 billion U.S. dollars) in Britain, Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said in a statement the figures "show that,
despite many people's concerns over currency exchange rates,
Britain remains a very popular tourism destination."
</P>
<P>
He attributed the rise of tourists to British fashion, design,
music and film, all part of the "Cool Britannia" explosion that
has seen London crowned the most "happening" city in the world.
</P>
<P>
Of recent film releases Clarke highlighted "The Full Monty",
which tells a story of jobless steel workers becoming strippers in
the northern city of Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
"I have no doubt that Sheffield will see tourists in search of
("Full Monty" star) Robert Carlyle and his compatriots," Clarke
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
