<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Completes Capital Construction Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China witnessed stable growth in
investments during the five year period from 1993 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
The period witnessed the completion of over 260,000 key capital
construction projects and renovation of an additon 170,000
projects.
</P>
<P>
Information released by the State Statistical Bureau today
indicated that investments for the period stood at 9,840.7 billion
yuan (1,185.6 billion US dollars) in fixed assets, that in 1997
topped 2,530 billion yuan (304.8 billion US dollars), up 10.1
percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Increased production capacities resulting from capital
construction during the five year period included: 88.72 million
tons of coal, 80.06 million tons of oil, 73.14 million kw of
power, 1.63 million cu.m of timber, railways stretching 6,409 km,
327,400 automobiles and an increased cargo handling capacity for
ports of 355.59 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Completed projects included the Beijing-Kowloon and
Nanning-Kunming railways, the Shanghai-Ningbo Expressway, Qinshan
Nuclear Power Station, No 2 Power Plant in Shentou, Shanxi
Province, and the first-phase project of Qianwan Harbor in
Qingdao, Shandong province. Projects scheduled for completion in
the next century include the Three Gorges Dam on the Yangtze
River, the Shenhua Project and the Xiaolangdi Power Station on the
Yellow River.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
