<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Siamese Twins Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian Siamese twins
who were successfully separated in South Africa in December
returned home Wednesday after spending more than five months at a
Pretoria hospital.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since their birth 13 months ago, Luka and
Joseph Banda will be able to live in their home in Matete
village, Zambia, with their laborer father and five other
siblings.
</P>
<P>
The nursing staff of Garankuwa Hospital, where the boys were
separated, went to Johannesburg International Airport Wednesday
morning to bid the boys and their mother farewell, the South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Luka and Joseph, who had been joined at the craniums, were
separated in a marathon 30-hour operation performed by a
50-member team of surgeons from South Africa, the United States
and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The boys will have to wear protective head gear because of
skull defects caused by the operation, until rectifying surgery
is carried out -- probably at the age of two.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to lead normal lives after that.
</P>
<P>
Garankuwa Hospital spokeswoman Babe Mosuwe said the twins were
in good physical health. They talk, smile, play and eat just like
any other one-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
However, they are unable to sit without support as their neck
muscles have not yet developed fully.
</P>
<P>
Since the operations, the boys had undergone a skin graft, and
pipes were inserted into their skulls to drain cerebral-spinal
fluid.
</P>
<P>
Mosuwe said the doctors were confident that the boys would not
develop any major complications and they would not have to return
to Garankuwa Hospital within a year.
</P>
<P>
The separation operation has been described as the first of
such in medical history that did not experience any major
complications.
</P>
<P>
The operation, which cost about 220,000 Rand (44,600 U.S.
Dollars), was done in South Africa at the request of the Zambian
government, since Zambia did not have the necessary facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Approves Measure to Lower Drinking Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday
approved a measure that would set a national standard for drunk
driving and punish states that don't abide by it with a loss of
highway funds.
</P>
<P>
The senators voted 62-32 to amend a major highway spending
bill, calling on all states to set 0.08 percent as the
blood-alcohol level at which a driver is declared legally drunk.
States that fail to do so by October 2001 would losing 5 percent
of their share of federal highway spending, with the penalty going
up to 10 percent at a later date.
</P>
<P>
Senator Frank Lautenberg, a chief sponsor of the amendment,
said, "Drunk driving is a crime, like assault, like shooting at
someone, like murder and it should be treated with the same
severity."
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the measure expressed concern that the punishments
were too harsh and said the federal government shouldn't be
forcing standards on states.
</P>
<P>
The issue is also likely to come up in the House when it takes
up the highway bill, probably later this month.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton strongly endorsed the legislation at a
White House gathering Tuesday. He announced that he was asking
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater to conduct a study on
enforcing the 0.08 percent limit on federal lands such as national
parks and military bases.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 15 states enforce 0.08 percent blood-alcohol levels,
while the other 35 states set the drunk driving standard at a
higher 0.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, more than 17,100 people died in alcohol-related
vehicle crashes nationwide, about 41 percent of all traffic
deaths, officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
Supporters said the amendment could save 600 lives a year if
the entire nation abided by the 0.08 percent level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
