<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Minister Criticizes National Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Public Service, Labor
and Social Welfare Minister Florence Chitauro Wednesday said a
confrontation between the government and labor movement would not
help resolve the pressing economic problems facing the country.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed on national radio during a phone-in program,
Chitauro said the government, individuals and private business
were prejudiced millions of Dollars in lost production due to
nationwide work stoppages.
</P>
<P>
The two-day national strike which started on Tuesday was
organized by the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) to
press the government into scrapping a 2.5 percentage sales tax
effected late last year, remove developmental levy and reduce the
prices of all basis commodities.
</P>
<P>
"If these stayaways, strikes and demonstrations we are
experiencing had no negative effect on the economy we would
simply ignore them," said the minister, adding "It is not
demonstrations against the government or even stayaways and
boycotts that will reduce the price hikes and taxes."
</P>
<P>
She said, however, there was always room for negotiations with
the labor movement to resolve the issue of price increases and
tax hikes.
</P>
<P>
"Any dispute should be resolved through dialogue. We are ready
and willing to negotiate with the trade union," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said:"The problem with the ZCTU is that they want to
criticize the government without offering any solutions or
alternatives to the problems."
</P>
<P>
Chitauro urged the labor movement to promote a culture of
dialogue with the government and other interested stakeholders to
resolve problems.
</P>
<P>
She said the issues of taxes should be discussed by members of
parliament as the elected representatives of people who should
take the matter up with government ministers.
</P>
<P>
On price increases, the miniter said that it was not the
government that pegs prices as these were determined by market
forces because of the now liberalized economy.
</P>
<P>
The mass strike Wednesday entered second day, causing most
businesses in the country closure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
