<HEADLINE> Moi Urges Banks to End Workers' Strike in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has urged employees of banks to end their strike starting last
Friday through dialogue Wednesday when union leaders called a
general strike.
</P>
<P>
Moi made the remarks at a meeting of the ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
After a while, union leaders made the new strike call at a
press conference, partly in response to Tuesday's governmental
decision on the sacking of some 15,000 striking bank workers who
were seeking for the scrapping of new tax rises on their soft
loans and allowances.
</P>
<P>
"A general strike is the decision reached by the labor
movement in this country," Central Organization of Trade Unions
(COTU) Assistant Secretary-General George Odiko said.
</P>
<P>
The umbrella body said it will announce a strike date and hold
a rally in capital Nairobi Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said that employees in Kenya Posts &AMP;
Telecommunications Corporation (KPTC) and the pension agency
National Social Security Fund (NSSF) were joining the strike in
sympathy with bank staff.
</P>
<P>
The NSSF began its protest on Tuesday, the KPTC planned to
join on Friday, and the Kenya Power &AMP; Lighting Corporation staff
planned to join the strike next week, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The strikers from at least 53 banks across the eastern African
country were demanding the government to quickly rescind the new
22 percent interest rate imposed on their loans and allowances,
</P>
<P>
They vowed at the beginning of the strike that they would not
return to work until the government called off the decision on
the new tax hike.
</P>
<P>
Most of major banks in Kenya, including the Commercial Bank,
Development Bank and Barclays Bank, remained closed Wednesday on
the fifth day of the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
