<HEADLINE> S. Africa Ranks 7th Most Competitive in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has been placed
7th in the competitive index of 23 African countries, South
African Press Association quoted the World Economic Forum as
reporting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Releasing its Africa competitiveness report for 1998, the
forum praised South Africa for its peaceful transition to
democratic rule since 1994.
</P>
<P>
While growth in economic terms has not been particularly high,
South Africa has maintained stability under circumstances which
most observers had expected would lead to civil unrest, the forum
said.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius, which has averaged an annual growth rate of six
percent, was ranked first. The island country was also cited as
one of th best off-shore locations for business.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia, which has had an average growth rate of 4.5 percent
in the past 10 years and a real gross domestic product of nearly
14 billion U.S. dollars, was placed second.
</P>
<P>
Botswana, previously classified as one of the world's
impoverished countries, was placed third. It has turned around
over the past three decades to earn the country a position in the
World Bank's group of medium income countries. Its 4.6 percent
GDP is Africa's fourth hightest.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, bordering with South Africa and Botswana, numbers
fourth in the rankings. Its export-oriented economy has ensured
the country of a modest per capita growth of two percent.
</P>
<P>
Overall competitiveness in the report was based on six
indices, which included openness, finance, labor, infrastructure
and institutions.
</P>
<P>
Other countries featured in the report are Morocco, Egypt,
Swaziland, Zimbabwe, Burkina Faso, Ghana, Angola, Cameroon,
Nigeria, Lesotho, Cote D' Ivoire, Zambia, Kenya, Malawi, Uganda,
Tanzania, Ethiopia and Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
