<HEADLINE> France Not to Extradite Former Italian Extreme-Left </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- France will not extradite the former
Italian extreme-left militants seeking refuge on its territory and
wanted by Italian judicial authorities for violent activities in
1970s, said French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jospin made the statement after 11 former Italian
extreme-leftwing militants living in exile in France appealed to
President Jacques Chirac and him for guaranteeing their
"legitimate stay" in France.
</P>
<P>
After Italy entered in December the Schengen space which
abolishes border control among European countries, three members
of former Italian extreme-left militants have been arrested by
French police in Paris and Bordeaux under obligation of the
Schengen agreement on judicial cooperations among signatory
countries.
</P>
<P>
Two of them have been released while one of them is waiting for
a court decision Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the lawyer representing the exiles, Jean-Jacques
de Felice, Jospin affirmed his government commitment to the
decision made in 1985 by President Francois Mitterrand not to
extradite the "persons who have renounced their former
activities."
</P>
<P>
"My government does not have the intention to change the
attitude which has been that of France up to now. That is why it
has not given and will not give right to any demand of extradition
of any of the Italian nationals who are in our country under the
conditions which I have previously indicated," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
