<HEADLINE> UN Chief to Visit Lebanon on Regional Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz announced on Wednesday that the United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan would visit Lebanon on March 20 as part of his
Middle East tour.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz told a press conference that during the visit, Annan
would hold talks with Lebanese leaders on the stalled Middle East
peace process, including the issue of south Lebanon currently
occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Annan's visit will come two days before the 20th anniversary of
the adoption of the U.N. Security Council Resolution 425, which
calls for an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a so-called security zone with an area of more
than 1,000 square kilometers in south Lebanon in 1985 to allegedly
protect its northern territory from cross-border attacks by Muslim
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Observers here have expected that the U.N. chief would carry
some ideas for the implementation of the resolution.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Lebanon, Annan will also inaugurate a
regional office for a U.N. agency, Boueiz added.
</P>
<P>
Annan originally planned to tour the region last month, but was
forced to put off the visit to deal with the Iraqi crisis over
U.N. arms inspections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
