<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Barings Directors Banned for up to 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- British government has disqualified
two former directors of Barings, the merchant bank which collapsed
three years ago following unauthorized trading activities by Nick
Leeson, from acting as company directors.
</P>
<P>
Several national newspapers reported Wednesday that Ex-chief
executive Peter Norris has been disqualified from acting as a
company director for four years while former treasurer Tony Hawes
is banned for five years by the Department of Trade and Industry
(DTI) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This sends a clear message to business. Directors must take
their responsibilities seriously -- there can be no passing the
buck. This message should be pinned up in every boardroom," said
competition and consumer affairs Minister Nigel Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
He added: "Nobody should be let in any doubt that we will act
wherever there are serious failings by directors".
</P>
<P>
It was reported that so far six former executives at Barings
have been temporarily disqualified from acting as company
directors. The DTI is expected to bring actions against 10 former
executives.
</P>
<P>
The DTI alleges that Norris failed to ensure Leeson's
activities were properly monitored or controlled despite his
awareness of a number of warning signs.
</P>
<P>
It also accused Hawes of failing to ensure that the provision
of massive amounts of funding to Leeson in Singapore was ever
properly understood, controlled and reconciled in Barings'
accounts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
