<HEADLINE> Britain Pledges to Help Save the Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain has pledged to help
bring the Middle East peace process back on track and do
something to help move the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks
forward.
</P>
<P>
This pledge was made by British Prime Minister Tony Blair in
his letter to Yasser Arafat, Chairman of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) and delivered on Wednesday by British Consul
General in Jerusalem to Arafat in Gaza, according to Jerusalem
Media and Communication Center (JMCC).
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Blair said that Britain worries about the
impasse of the peace process and it will try its best to help
bring it back on track.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe that Britain is preparing to
pay the diplomatic bill to the Arab world for its active
participation in the military build-up during the Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Britain, which holds the current presidency of
the European union (EU), have already signaled they will take
full advantage of at least two high-profile opportunities to
underscore these points in the coming weeks, when British Foreign
secretary Robin Cook visits Israel later this month and Blair
visits Israel in April to take part in Israel's 50th anniversary
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Both Cook abd Blair are scheduled to meet Arafat in Gaza and
they are expected to tell Arafat that Britain's current government
will be far tougher than previous one in blaming what they
perceive to be foot-dragging by the Israeli government in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat on Wednesday also met with Terry Larsen, the Norwegian
Envoy to the peace process at his Gaza headquarters, during which
the two discussed the latest developments in the process, JMCC
said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian talks on Gaza airport, sea port and the safe
passage linking the West Bank and Gaza Strip are continuing, but
no specific results have been reached so far.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian Safe-passage Route Committee,
comprising military and security officials of both sides, met
again secretly on Wednesday, but no progress was reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
