<HEADLINE> Emergency Meeting on Kosovo to Be Held in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the Contact
Group on former Yugoslavia will hold an emergency meeting on the
Kosovo crisis in London next Monday, British Foreign Office
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The British government made the announcement amid worsening
tensions in Kosovo, Serbian Republic of Yugoslavia where some 20
ethnic Albanians have keen killed in violence recently.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who is on a visit to the
former Yugoslavian region, is expected to chair the meeting of the
Contact Group -- comprising the United States, Russia,Britain,
France, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special Balkan envoy Robert Gelbard was quoted by the
Reuters as saying early Wednesday that the six-nation Contact
Group could threaten new sanctions against Yugoslavia if President
Slobodan Milosevic failed to ensure the current crisis with the
ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo were resolved peacefully.
</P>
<P>
It would be the first such emergency ministerial talks since
the end of the Bosnian war in 1995, underlining the wide-spread
concern about worsening situation in Kosovo, where 90 percent of
its population are ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
