<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador Wu on Declaration on Human Rights Defenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Dialogue is one of the main reasons
leading to the Declaration on the Right and Responsibility of
Individuals, Groups and Organs of Society to Promote and Protect
Universally Recognized Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms
adopted by consensus here on Wednesday, Ambassador Wu Jianmin
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the declaration adopted at a meeting of the
drafting working group, the head of the Chinese delegation said
that the adoption by consensus of the declaration, known as the
Declaration on Human Rights Defenders one week before the 54th
session of the United Nations Human Rights Commission is
undoubtedly a valuable gift from the working group to the 50th
anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
Wu underlined three points which the international community
should learn from the experience of the working group:
</P>
<P>
-- Dialogue is better than confrontation.
</P>
<P>
In the drafting process of the past 14 years, members of the
working group refrained from confrontation, lecturing and having
one's own way. They engaged in patient dialogues to enhance mutual
understanding and bridge differences and finally reached
consensus.
</P>
<P>
One can well imagine if there had been no willingness for
dialogue, no interest in differing views and no stomach for
discussion, there would have been no consensus. The experience of
the working group once again proves that confrontation doesn't
help. Dialogue is the correct way to promote and protect human
rights.
</P>
<P>
-- Equality and mutual respect are an important guarantee for a
fruitful dialogue.
</P>
<P>
One other factor that contributes to the consensus is that the
parties concerned observed the principle of equality and mutual
respect in the drafting process. Although they were wide apart on
many issues, they managed to discuss their differences on the
basis of equality and mutual respect. They tried to understand and
accommodate each other's views and showed a degree of flexibility.
</P>
<P>
If some countries or a group of countries had insisted on a
declaration which only reflected their own position, they could
have pushed through a declaration by vote long ago. But that kind
of declaration would lack moral strength and a solid base for
implementation.
</P>
<P>
The one we have adopted today is a product of compromise. It
may not be considered an ideal document by individual countries.
But it is definitely the best result the international community
is able to achieve today, therefore it will exert more influence.
</P>
<P>
-- Cooperation is feasible if the principle of seeking common
ground while reserving differences is observed.
</P>
<P>
The prime objective of the Declaration on Human Rights
Defenders is to formulate a political framework for the activities
of individuals, groups and organs of society in the field of
promoting and protecting human rights.
</P>
<P>
Since different countries have different values, different
legislations and judicial practices, it's only natural for them to
have divergent views on some issues. However, we do share the same
views on many other issues.
</P>
<P>
During the past 14 years, in spite of many difficulties,
members of the working group never gave up their efforts to seek
common ground and to pursue the ultimate goal of reaching
consensus.
</P>
<P>
This fully shows that differences are not insurmountable, if
all concerned endeavor to seek common ground while reserving
differences. Common ground provides the basis for cooperation, and
makes consensus possible.
</P>
<P>
"The 54th session of the Human Rights Commission is about to
begin," Wu concluded. "We sincerely hope that all the members of
the working group will bring the spirit of engaging in equal
dialogue and seeking common ground to the Commission, and reject
the North-South confrontation which has been plaguing the
Commission for so long, with a view to putting the international
human rights activities on the sound course of dialogue and
cooperation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
