<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots Urged to Join Cyprus' Talks with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot government expressed hope
on Wednesday that the Turkish Cypriots would participate in the
upcoming accession negotiations with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it also put forward principles governing the Turkish
Cypriot joining of the government delegation.
</P>
<P>
"Under no circumstances should Turkish Cypriot participation
undermine the status of the Republic of Cyprus or imply in any way
direct or indirect recognition of the illegal entity in the
Turkish-occupied part of the island," Cypriot government spokesman
Christos Stylianides told a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government would consult with the Cypriot
political leadership, the Greek government and legal experts to
try to find a formula for Turkish Cypriot participation.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island to protect
the Turkish minorities after a failed coup by Greek Cypriots
seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is recognized only by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has invited the Turkish Cypriots to take
part in the accession talks with the EU, but was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides announced that former President George Vassiliou
would lead the Cypriot delegation in accession talks due to start
on March 31.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came shortly before EU External Relations
Commissioner Hans Van den Broek and British special envoy for
Cyprus David Hannay arrived here Wednesday night to discuss a
formula for the Turkish Cypriots to attend the EU accession talks.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has refused to
meet with them. He has accused the EU of sabotaging the U.N.-led
talks of the two communities by initiating the accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has claimed that if the "Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus" is recognized, "doors to negotiations will open." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
