<HEADLINE> King Hussein Urges Iraqi Compliance With UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan Wednesday
urged Iraq to fully abide by U.N. resolutions related to
dismantling weapons of mass destruction to avert any possible
U.S. military strike.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Jordanian king made the statement after talks with
his UAE counterpart Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan. He said
"the sole reply" to U.S. war talks "is Baghdad's full compliance
with the agreement Iraq signed with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan," the United Arab Emirates' official Wam news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The accord signed in Baghdad on February 23 was approved by the
U.N. Security Council Tuesday with the adoption of a
U.N. resolution warning Iraq of "servest consequences" if it fails
to give U.N. arms inspectors complete and unconditional access to
sites suspected of containing biological or chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton threatened Tuesday that Washington
will take military action against Baghdad if it did not implement
all U.N. Security Council resolutions related to dismantling
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Hussein, who arrived here Tuesday for a three-day visit, is to
leave for Oman Thursday. He said his visits to the two Gulf
countries were mainly aimed at exchanging views with the two
states' leaders on the latest developments in the Gulf region in
the light of the Iraq-U.N. agreement and discussing with them ways
of boosting Arab solidarity. 
</P>
