<HEADLINE> Primakov: Kosovo Event is Internal Affair of Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kosovo envent is Yugoslavia's
internal issue which has no direct bearing on the settlement
process in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after meeting with visiting
Polish counterpart, Bronislaw Geremek, the current OSCE chairman,
Primakov said that both he and his polish guest agreed that
terrorist activities in any form in Kosovo should be countered,
while conditions must be created for a dialogue between the
Yugoslav authorities and moderate Kosovo Albanian leaders who
regard the area as part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the resolution of this problem is imperative, the
Russian minister noted the need to "put an end to terrorist acts
by individual extremist groups" without launching a "large-scale
combat operation" on the part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers held the OSCE has a major role to
play in setting up a security system in Europe, and the system
cannot be hierarchical, according to Primakov.
</P>
<P>
On the NATO expansion, Geremek, for his part, said that Warsaw
and Moscow continue to differ on the issue. "Poland wants to join
NATO and simultaneously to have the best possible relations with
Russia," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Another report quoted a Russian Foreign Ministry source as
saying that Moscow is not considering sending a special envoy to
Yugoslavia and is negotiating with the Yugoslavian leadership via
the Russian Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Primakov plans to visit former Yugoslav republics after
mid-March, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Geremek arrived in Moscow on Tuesday night for a one-day
working visit to Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
