<HEADLINE> Qatar Plays Down Labor Dispute with Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Qatar played down the problems
facing the Egyptian laborers in Qatar on Wednesday and said it
would ensure their rights.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has paid the Egyptian workers leaving Qatar recently and
allow others to stay until they finish departure procedures,
Hussein al-Mulla, Qatari undersecretary of Housing and Civil
Service told reporters in Egyptian southern city Luxor on the
sidelines of the 25th Arab Labor Conference.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing reports that Egyptian workers have had hard times in
the oil-rich Gulf state, al-Mulla expressed Qatar's readiness to
examine any complaint submitted by Egyptian workers over their
remittances.
</P>
<P>
A great many of Egyptians have reportedly been fired by the
Qatari authorities since 1996 when Egypt was allegedly found to be
involved in a failed coup in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
To resolve the dispute and improve the bilateral relations, the
two Arab countries reached an agreement on Sunday to allow
Egyptian workers to return to Qatar, and to assess the prospects
to reopen the Qatari job market to Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
Al-Mulla hailed Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's invitation
for Emir of Qatar to visit Cairo as a fresh proof that the
bilateral ties "are faring well."
</P>
<P>
About 25,000 Egyptians are living in Qatar. 
</P>
