<HEADLINE> Germany Deports 117 Kosovo Albanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany Wednesday deported 117 ethnic
Albanians originated from the ex-Yugoslav area of Kosovo, where
ethnic Albanians and Serbs are on the verge of armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that at least 20 of the people
boarded a plane bound for Pristina, a main town of Kosovo, while
others being flew to Belgrade, including 77 persons from the
southern state of Bavaria alone.
</P>
<P>
Bavaria's council on refugee affairs criticized the
deportation, saying it was against the German law and Geneva
conventions to deport any person into a zone of danger.
</P>
<P>
The deportees had been denied refugee status in Germany. It is
reported that there are currently well over 50,000 Kosovo
Albanians in Germany, with more than 20,000 of them in Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
Dieter Schlee, the federal parliament's commissioner for Bosnian
refugees, earlier said that so far a total of 140,000 ethnic
Albanians had applied for refugee status in Germany.
</P>
<P>
German refugee tribunals have rejected most of the claims for
political asylum, noting that most of the Albanians were not
subject to persecution individually though their community is in
conflict with the Serbian state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
