<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Health Spending Low in Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's per capita health
spending of nine U.S. Dollars a year is much lower than Ghana's
14 Dollars and Kenya's 16 Dollars, the Federal Office of
Statistics (FOS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing 1990 as example, FOS said health spending accounted for
2.7 percent of the year's gross domestic product (GDP) in
Nigeria, 3.5 percent in Ghana and 4.3 percent in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, Nigerian children have poor health
much worse than in most other African countries, FOS said in a
publication entitled "Poverty and Welfare in Nigeria".
</P>
<P>
The publication, jointly produced by the National Planning
Commission of Nigeria and analyzed by the World Bank, says that
under-five mortality rate in Nigeria is 20 percent, compared with
15 percent and nine percent in Ghana and Kenya respectively.
</P>
<P>
It noted that one in every six children under five years had
at least one attack of diarrhoea in the previous two weeks with
little gender variation in Nigeria, which witnessed an infant
mortality of 11.4 percent in 1990, as against 7.4 percent in
Ghana and 5.9 percent in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
According to FOS, many households in Nigeria are unable to
provide adequate nutritious food for all family members, a
situation that has led to increasing malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
Widespread are childhood malnutrition and its consequences,
such as stunting, which are caused by poor diet, short birth
intervals and rampant diseases, it added.
</P>
<P>
"Yet almost 80 percent of infant deaths are caused by
preventable diseases including 10 percent of vaccine preventable
diseases, 25 percent diarrhoea and malaria, acute respiratory
infection which stood at 20 percent and five percent of low birth
weight," it said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that good ventilation in houses and early vaccinations
could help reduce the infant mortality rate by 20 percent and 10
percent respectively, it maintains that immunization coverage is
only 22 percent for children between 12 and 23 months.
</P>
<P>
The publication further noted that only 36 percent of people
in the rural areas have access to potable water, compared with 80
percent in urban centers, while 48 percent of the latter have no
access to adequate sanitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
