<HEADLINE> China Wins Bid for Zambian Copper Mine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM) announced here Wednesday that one of its copper mines has
been awarded to a Chinese corporation, who has won the bid.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, ZCCM Chairman Luke Mwananshiku, and Francis
Kaunda, chairman of the government privatization negotiating
team, announced that Chambishi mine has been won by the Foreign
Engineering and Construction Corporation of China.
</P>
<P>
The Chambishi mine is proved to have 33.5 million tons'
reserves of 2.55 percent copper.
</P>
<P>
Sources of the Chinese corporation told Xinhua that the
corporation is committed to the development of the mine over a
period of five years from close.
</P>
<P>
The corporation plans to re-establish the mine with a planned
production capacity of 3,000 tons of ore per day within the first
two years from close, and 6,000 tons after another two years, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Due to copper price falls in the international market and
outdated equipment, lack of investment and mismanagement, the
annual copper output in Zambia, one of the biggest
copper-producing countries in the world, has decreased gradually
to about 300,000 tons in recent years.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investments, advanced technology and
management to revive the stagnating copper production, the
government has invited foreign tenders for the ZCCM mines and
assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
