<HEADLINE> 80 Percent Nigerians Live Below Poverty Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- About 80 percent of the more than
100 million Nigerians now live below the poverty line, according
to a senior official from Family Economic Advancement Program
(FEAP), the country's poverty-alleviation organization.
</P>
<P>
The poverty line margin rose from 34 percent in 1992 to the
current rate following the dwindling of family income and weak
purchasing power, said FEAP Director-General Abdullahi Aliyu.
</P>
<P>
While inflation rate declined over the period, poverty
continued to increase, he said recently, quoted by the News
Agency of Nigeria Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, FEAP has carefully selected 140 projects
that could be executed by people living perpetually below the
poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of FEAP, he said, was to encourage local
industrial revolution based on re-orientation of the productive
sector at the grass-roots.
</P>
<P>
The program would create about two million jobs annually with
variables put in place, to ensure that by the year 2010, only
about 10 percent of the total population would be below the
poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Currently, six banks have been selected to disburse about
seven billion Naira (about 87 million U.S. Dollars) earmarked by
the government for the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
