<HEADLINE> UN Seeks Over $11 Million to Meet Sierra Leone's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations on
Wednesday appealed for 11.2 million U.S. dollars to meet priority
humanitarian needs in Sierra Leone over the next three months, as
the country recovers form the forceful removal of the military
junta.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was prepared after two United Nations missions
returned form the country last month and determined that the
current humanitarian situation in Sierra Leone remains serious.
</P>
<P>
In the country, the primary health care system has been
devastated by a lack of supplies, looting and the exodus of
medical personnel. Widespread neglect of water and sanitation
facilities has increased the exposure of hundreds of thousands to
disease.
</P>
<P>
The missions also found that normal distribution of food to
vulnerable groups has been disrupted, affecting children in
particular. Many children have also been exposed to acts of
violence after being sent into battle as combatants.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations appeal seeks funds for priority intervention
to support agriculture, re-establish basic health and education
service, ensure the resumption of food aid distributions and to
provide protection and assistance to the most vulnerable groups
affected by the current conflict.  
</P>
</TEXT>
