<HEADLINE> Egypt Sets up First Mobile Phone Service Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Egypt Wednesday set up its first
company to operate the nation's 100,000-subscriber mobile
telephone network, in a move to privatize its telecommunications
industry, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-based Mobile Telephone Services Co. will install,
manage, operate, develop and maintain the mobile telephone network
(GSM) in collaboration with the Telecom Egypt, the Egyptian
telecommunications authority, and undertake all operations related
to this service.
</P>
<P>
Public subscriptions had been invited to cover 180 million
pounds (about 53 million U.S. dollars), or 30 percent, of the
company's issued shares, totaling 600 million pounds (176 million
dollars). Four major Egyptian banks will purchase 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shares were priced at 10 pounds (3 dollars) each, with only 2.50
pounds (0.7 dollars) due at subscription and with a minimum
purchase of just 50 shares. The maximum purchase was set at
600,000 shares, or 3.3 percent of the 18 million share offering.
</P>
<P>
The initial public offering for the company's shares which
closed last week reportedly was oversubcribed by more than 50
times. 
