<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Halts New Taxes to End Bank Staff's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae announced Wednesday evening the suspension of new tax
hikes on bank workers' loans and allowances, hours after union
leaders called a general strike across the country.
</P>
<P>
"I have decided to exercise my option under the law and
directed the Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA) to suspend the
implementation of the increase until the matter is brought to
parliament for review," said Nyachae in a local TV news
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi also urged
bank employees to end their five-day strike through dialog and
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Some 15,000 bank staff from 53 banks around the country took
part in the strike, demanding the scrapping of the new 22 percent
interest rate imposed on their soft loans and allowances.
</P>
<P>
In response, the bank employers announced Tuesday that all the
striking workers were fired, which has triggered off a possible
general strike.
</P>
<P>
In sympathy with bank staff, employees in Kenya Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (KPTC) planned to join the strike
Friday while the pension agency, National Social Security Fund
(NSSF), began its protest Tuesday, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
The strikers vowed at the beginning of the strike that they
would not return to work until the government called off the
decision on the new tax hike.
</P>
<P>
Most of the major banks in Kenya, including the National Bank
of Kenya, Commercial Bank, Development Bank and Barclays Bank,
remained closed or only offered very slow and limited services
Wednesday. 
</P>
