<HEADLINE> Suspected German Nazi Criminal Arrested in Stuttgart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- German police have arrested in
Stuttgart a suspected German Nazi criminal who was involved in the
killing of over 70,000 people, mostly Jews, in Poland during World
War II, it was announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Justice officials said police arrested the 78-year-old man
Tuesday. He was a member of the Command of the Nazi Security
Police in Lublin, Poland, and of the Gestapo secret police.
</P>
<P>
They said the man, whose name had never been listed as a wanted
suspect, admitted, while testifying in another investigation into
Nazi crimes, that he had personally shot dead 500 people,
including children, in November 1943 at the Majdanek concentration
camp.
</P>
<P>
The suspect, who lived in Kazakhstan till 1991 and then
migrated to Germany, was interviewed in 1996 by German prosecutors
at the request of the Scotland Yard in connection with a Nazi crime
investigation in Britain.
</P>
<P>
He incriminated himself when being interrogated again in
Dortmund last year.
</P>
<P>
A commercial radio station in Mannheim gave the man's name as
Alfons Goetzfried, on which the state prosecutors declined to
comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
