<P>
BAGHDAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
Wednesday evening met with French president's special envoy
Bertrand Dufourcq to discuss the implementation of the agreement
signed by U.N. Chief Kofi Annan and Iraq on arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq, who arrived here Tuesday evening, handed over
President Jacques Chirac's letter to Saddam during the
meeting. Saddam said he would write a letter in reply and send his
special envoy to Paris with the letter.
</P>
<P>
Chirac reportedly said in his letter that Iraq has the right
to return to the international community on the condition that it
plays the game according to the rule.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq, also secretary general of French Foreign Ministry,
stressed the significance his country attaches to the complete and
rapid implementation of the agreement signed late last month by
Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Iraq agrees to grant a special U.N.
inspection group free, unconditional and unrestricted access to its
presidential palaces. The group will comprise of senior diplomats
appointed by Annan and experts drawn from the U.N. Special
Commission in charge of eliminating Iraq's banned weapons and the
International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq told reporters Tuesday upon his arrival at the Saddam
International Airport that he would raise the perspective of the
lifting of the U.N. sanctions as soon as Iraq has fulfilled its
obligation in terms of elimination of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution on Monday which
approves the agreement and warns of the "severest consequences"
if Iraq violates the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq visited Baghdad as French president's special envoy
early last month to help find a diplomatic solution to the then
standoff between Iraq and the United States over U.N. weapons
inspection. 
</P>
