<HEADLINE> Turkey Denies Violating Greek Air Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Wednesday denied the
Greek allegations that Turkish warplanes violated Greek air space
over the Aegean Sea, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular news briefing, Turkish Foreign Ministry
deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that Turkish military jets
were conducting routine training at that time, describing the
accusations as "groundless."
</P>
<P>
Atacanli said that Greece had made such allegations many
times, adding that this formulation arose from Greece's unilateral
and illegal announcement of a 10-mile air space.
</P>
<P>
The Greek News Agency reported that Turkish warplanes crossed
the Flight Information Region line without permission on
Tuesday, constituting a violation of Greek airspace.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry has repeatedly emphasized that Turkey
does not recognize Greece's 10-mile air space as it is against the
principles of international law.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds due to their disputes over
the limits of air space, sovereignty over islets in the Aegean as
well as the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Warplanes and naval vessels of the two countries are often
involved in minor clashes over and in the Aegean, triggering off
endless accusations.
</P>
<P>
Their disagreement about an uninhabited small island in the
Aegean brought the two rivals to the brink of war in early
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
