<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Denies Unwarranted Massive Detentions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Interior Minister Habib
el-Adly Wednesday dismissed charges that his ministry has made
massive arrests without trial and rampant telephone buggings in
the country.
</P>
<P>
El-Adly told the weekly illustrated magazine Al-Mussawar that
the claim by the Cairo-based Egyptian Human Rights Organizations
about 34,000 Egyptians were detained without trial was
"fictitious."
</P>
<P>
"Detentions are made after careful calculations and we keep
suspects in a safe place to pre-empt crimes. Not even one suspect
has been detained without a prior court permission because
detainees have the right to contest their detention decision in
court within 30 days," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The minister also scoffed at claims that 100,000 telephones
were bugged, saying the figure is "absolutely wrong and
exaggerated."
</P>
<P>
"To do that we need an additional ministry of communications
devoted for this job ... if there is telephone tapping it is done
with permission of a court and a judge for a certain period of
time and a certain reason," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government has tightened the noose over Muslim militants
since 58 foreign tourists were slaughtered by six Muslim militants
in front of the Hatshepsut Temple in the country's largest
archeological city of Loxor on November 17.
</P>
<P>
But some human rights groups accused Egypt of abusing the
Emergency Law which was enacted after former President Anwar Sadat
was assassinated in 1981 to make indiscriminate arrests, mass
detentions and military trials of civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
