<HEADLINE> S. African Cabinet Approves Info Tech Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- South African cabinet
Wednesday approved a framework proposal for the development of a
national information and communication technology strategy, the
Department of Post and Telecommunications said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the key elements of the strategy
are:
</P>
<P>
-- improving the technology capability of the government
through the creation of a number of technology projects based on
a high-speed fiber-optic backbone developed by the
telecommunications giant Telkom;
</P>
<P>
-- improving service offered to all citizens by providing a
one-stop shop through the use of smart cards and public
information terminals; and
</P>
<P>
-- developing legislation on cyber laws such as digital
signatures and encryption that will allow e-commerce to become a
reality.
</P>
<P>
"The use of information would allow the government to offer an
efficient, standardized service to citizens in all areas on a
24-hour basis," the statement quoted Post and Telecommunications
Minister Jay Naidoo as saying.
</P>
<P>
This will be done through the introduction of public
information terminals and community information centers, said
Naidoo.
</P>
<P>
"The result of this will be a much more dynamic interaction
between government and the people and see a substantial reduction
in bureaucracy."
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet decision meant the government could begin
the mammoth task of coordinating the development of the strategy
as well as individual projects to be introduced in the short,
medium and long term.
</P>
<P>
"New key projects and existing projects will be integrated
into the strategy," said Naidoo.
</P>
<P>
He said a cost benefit analysis would be presented to the
government budgetary committee during the next budgetary cycle.
</P>
<P>
Several government departments are to be involved in the
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
