<HEADLINE> Iraq Demands Using Iraqi Equipment in UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has demanded the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) use Iraqi, not foreign
equipment in its mission to avoid violating Iraq's sovereignty,
the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq made the demand in a letter sent by Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, INA
said.
</P>
<P>
But it did not say what are the equipment.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, al-Sahhaf lodged a protest against U-2 spy plane
of the United States flying in Iraq's air space.
</P>
<P>
He accused the U-2 plane of infringing Iraq's space under the
cover that it carries out inspection mission in the air for the
UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, arms inspection teams of the UNSCOM went on with
their mission Wednesday, Husam Mohammed Ameen, director general of
the Iraqi National Monitoring Directorate assisting the UNSCOM,
told INA.
</P>
<P>
Ten teams paid surprising visit to 12 sites and accomplished
their task under the cooperation of the Iraqi side, Ameen said.
</P>
<P>
One of the teams carried out its inspection work in the air by
helicopter, he said, adding that no incidents happened.
</P>
<P>
A technical team dispatched by the International Atomic Energy
Agency (IAEA) held discussion about the inspection of nuclear
weapons with the Iraqi side during the day, the Iraqi official
said, without disclosing details.
</P>
<P>
The IAEA team arrived in Iraq two weeks ago and has been
carrying out its work smoothly, he added.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM is to verify that Iraq has destroyed all its
nuclear, chemical and biological weapons of mass destruction. Only
then will the U.N. lift the economic sanctions imposed on Iraq in
1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
