<HEADLINE> Quality Education Fund Starts Operation in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Quality Education Fund was
launched here Thursday to encourage innovation, competition and
self-motivated reform in Hong Kong primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
The 5-billion-HK dollar (641 million U.S. dollars) fund was
initiated by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa in his maiden policy
address last October.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the launching ceremony Thursday, acting Chief
Executive Anson Chan noted that basic education is the pillar of
social progress and that the government has all along attached
great importance to it.
</P>
<P>
Substantial resources are devoted to this area every year, she
said, stressing that the financial provision for basic education
will increase by more than 16 percent this year over the previous
one, as shown in the 1998-1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
She said the fund will mark a significant step forward in the
government's endeavor on the educational front.
</P>
<P>
"It is aimed at encouraging the education community to take the
initiative in introducing improvements and innovations to school
education" by providing a flexible funding mechanism, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the fund steering committee, Irving Koo Yee-yin,
also said after the ceremony that the fund will provide an
effective channel to fund worthwhile projects to improve the
quality of basic education in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Attending the ceremony were around 1,500 heads of nurseries,
kindergartens and primary, secondary and special schools,
representatives of major school sponsoring bodies, teachers'
associations and education bodies and academics.
</P>
<P>
Schools, education bodies and teaching professionals will be
invited between March 5 and April 30 to submit applications to the
fund for funding innovative projects. The first batch of grants
are expected to be released by the end of June.  
</P>
</TEXT>
