<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Finance Ministry Officials Arrested Over Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo prosecutors arrested Thursday
two Finance Ministry bureaucrats for allegedly taking bribes from
two major securities firms and a major commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Prosecutors Office identified one of the two
officials in custody as Takashi Sakakibara, 38, deputy director of
the Securities Bureau's general affairs section.
</P>
<P>
The other official was Toshio Miyano, 51, of the Securities and
Exchange Surveillance Commission.
</P>
<P>
Sakakibara and Miyano are suspected of receiving a total of
4.86 million yen (about 38,300 U.S. dollars) in bribes in the form
of wining, dining and rounds of golf, the office said.
</P>
<P>
According to prosecution sources, involved in the case were
officials from Nomura Securities Co., Daiwa Securities Co. and
Sumitomo Bank, who were being questioned by investigators.
</P>
<P>
The probe into the entertaining spendings of current and former
MOF officials began last September.
</P>
<P>
Two bank inspectors at the Finance Ministry and a former career
official at the ministry were arrested earlier this year on
suspicion of taking bribes from banks and brokerage houses.
</P>
<P>
Expressing regret over the arrests, Chief Cabinet Secretary
Kanezo Murao said the government will present a bill on the ethics
of public servants to the Diet, or parliament, next month.
</P>
<P>
The government will take this opportunity to drastically reform
the Finance Ministry and enforce discipline on its employees, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
