<HEADLINE> Official Grain Prices to Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The central government is
determined to stablize the prices for state grain purchases in
1998 in order to protect the interests and enthusiasm of the
nation's farmers, according to an official from the State Planning
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that successive bumper grain harvests have
contributed greatly to sustained, rapid and healthy national
economic development.
</P>
<P>
He advised local governments in all provinces, ethnic
autonomous regions and municipalities to base this year's prices
on 1997 levels.
</P>
<P>
Differing varieties and qualities of grain should be priced
accordingly, said the official, adding that quality items should
quite obviously be subject to higher prices.
</P>
<P>
Pricing should meet market requirements and protect the
enthusiasm and interests of farmers, according to the official. He
stressed that protective prices should be adopted when costs
exceed market prices in order that farmers have the capacity to
produce sufficient seeds and ensure their own subsistence.
</P>
<P>
He urged local governments to decide on grain purchase prices
at the earliest possible date. He also called for guaranteeing
access to means of production, including seeds, fertilizer and
chemicals, and for eliminating illegal charges and levies on
farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
