<HEADLINE> Last Tribal Rebels Lay Down Arms in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 218 Bangladeshi tribal
rebels laid down their arms Thursday in the fourth and last phase
of their ceremonial surrender, the national news agency BSS
reported.
</P>
<P>
The ceremonial handing-over of weapons by the last batch of
tribal guerrillas in Daduckchhari, Khagrachhari, Southeast
Bangladesh, marked the end of the rebel arms deposit process.
</P>
<P>
With Thursday's surrender, all the 1,943 men of the Parbatya
Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS) have laid down their arms.
The disbandment of Shanti Bahini, the armed wing of the PCJSS,
brought an end to two decades of bush war in the Chittagong Hill
Tracts.
</P>
<P>
"It is a historic day for the nation as it marks the end of the
bush life of all the PCJSS men," said Civil Aviation and Tourism
Minister Mosharraf Hossain.
</P>
<P>
Under a peace accord signed last December between the
government and the PCJSS, the first phase of arms surrender by the
tribal rebels was held on February 10 when Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina received weapons from the first batch of more than 700
Shanti Bahini members.
</P>
<P>
The second and third phases of arms surrender were held on
February 16 and 22 respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
