<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Dramatic Sales Drop Shakes Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp., the world's
largest computer chip manufacturer, said Wednesday its revenues in
the year's first quarter would be 10 percent less than expected.
</P>
<P>
The California-based Intel said in January its sales in the
first quarter would be about 6.5 billion U.S. dollars but the
latest warning indicated sales would be down to some 5.85 billion.
</P>
<P>
The warning shook the high-tech industry and fueled fears that
the industry is headed toward a broad-based slowdown.
</P>
<P>
What is more alarming, the giant could not give a reason for
the dramatic drop in sales. Intel's microprocessors power more
than 85 percent of personal computers, or PCs, worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Other major companies have also reported disappointing earnings
in recent months. But up to now, most market research firms had
been predicting a fairly robust 15 to 20 percent growth rate in PC
sales for 1998, even accounting for the meltdown in the Asian
economy.
</P>
<P>
An Intel spokesman said computer companies are buying far fewer
chips than Intel expected. Most of the shortfall is occurring in
Europe and North America. Industry observers estimated Intel will
end up selling 2.5 million fewer chips than previously expected
this quarter.
</P>
<P>
PC prices have been dropping steadily for the past two years,
mostly the result of lower prices for components such as disk
drives, microprocessors and memory chips. There is some evidence
that more recent price cuts, however, are a response to lower
sales volume.
</P>
<P>
Some industry analysts say Intel's sales decline could reflect
the company's slowness to react to changing market conditions,
particularly the emergence of the sub-1,000 dollars PC.
</P>
<P>
Intel's announcement had already affected share prices. While
after-hours trading volumes were extremely small, Intel's stock
dropped by as much as 10 dollars a share. Dell, IBM and other
computer companies also dropped steeply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seizinger Wins World Cup Downhill and Super-G </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Katja Seizinger won the
downhill and Super-G Alpine Skiing World Cup titles on Thursday
after two races due to be held next weekend in Morzine of France
were cancelled for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
"Bad weather conditions and especially strong winds which blew
violently this week have torn the safety nets along the piste. It
is impossible to re-install the safety devices in time for the
races," organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Seizinger now can no longer be beaten in the downhill and
Super-G classifications since the rest of the tow races over the
weakend could not be postponed as World Cup finals are slated next
week in Crans-Montana.
</P>
<P>
The German downhill and combined Olympic champion has already
won the downhill World Cup three times and the Super-G crown four
times.
</P>
<P>
But she will have to wait for the four Crans-Montana races to
know whether she can claim her second overall World Cup
title. Seizinger currently leads compatriots Martina Ertl and
Hilde Gerg by 267 and 329 points, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
