<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Takes Steps to Cut Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae Thursday announced a "firm and painful" package of tax
increases in a bid to reduce the budget deficit and get the
country's economy back on right track.
</P>
<P>
The wide-ranging package raises value-added tax and fuel
prices. It also includes a drive on tax arrears and a freeze on
all duty waivers for charitable agencies.
</P>
<P>
The move came just one day after the government's failure to
raise revenue by imposing higher tax rates on bank employees'
soft loans and allowances. The efforts to raise revenue were
suspended Wednesday due to a nationwide bank staff strike
starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The implementation of these macro-economic and structural
reform measures is essential to enhance economic growth, limit
the rate of inflation to a manageable level and enable interest
rates to fall," Nyachae said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's budget deficit is estimated to rise to 3.9 percent of
the gross domestic product (GDP) in fiscal 1997/98 (July/June)
from a target of 1.7 percent (the same as the 96/97 figure) if
emergency measures are not put in place.
</P>
<P>
The proposed package includes:
</P>
<P>
-- Reduction of non-wage, non-interest recurrent and
development expenditure by a total of 3.4 billion Shillings;
</P>
<P>
-- A rise in the lower rate of VAT to 12 percent from 10
percent, and in the higher rate to 17 percent from 16 percent;
</P>
<P>
-- An increase in duties on petrol by 3.1 Shillings per liter,
on automotive diesel by 2.5 Shillings per liter and on kerosene
by 1.15 Shillings per liter;
</P>
<P>
-- A complete freeze on all duty and VAT waivers: all
donations for non-governmental organizations will be on a tax
basis, except for medicines and items imported by U.N. refugee
agency UNHCR and U.N. food aid agency WFP;
</P>
<P>
-- Tighter administration of customs procedures, especially
customs bonds and transit cargo, and collection of all income tax
and VAT arrears;
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government would also maintain a strict monetary policy
and accelerate its privatization of state firms, said Nyachae.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi, who won a final five-year term in
the December elections, has repeatedly urged his fellow people to
tighten their belts in the coming tough economic year.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund last week painted a bleak
picture of the country's economy, with its budget deficit
ballooning, GDP growth and currency declining, interest rates
climbing and inflation rising well beyond projections.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Kenyan government has agreed to cut
spending by 10 billion Shillings (165 million U.S. Dollars) in
order to keep the budget deficit at about 2.4 percent of GDP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
