<HEADLINE> Philippine Government to Regulate Sugar Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will take
over the importation of sugar from the private sector next year to
avoid over-import of cheap foreign sugar, Sugar Regulatory
Administrator Michael Suarez said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Suarez said Agriculture Secretary Salvador Escudero had already
given the Sugar Regulatory Administration the go-ahead with a plan
for government importation of sugar as long as there is
consultation with sugar producers.
</P>
<P>
Suarez said the country's sugar producers have urged his
administration to regulate the importation of sugar this year.
</P>
<P>
Suarez said he is going to meet with the National Council of
Sugar Producers to discuss the matter so that next year's
importation of sugar would be done through the National Food
Authority.
</P>
<P>
But he said it would already be too late for the government to
take over sugar importation this year as the planned imports of
some 150,000 metric tons should come in as early as June to ensure
a buffer stock during the months of July, August and September.
</P>
<P>
Under government control, an orderly sugar importation could be
assured, Suarez said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has been troubled by a glut of sugar supply
during the past two years as the private sector was empowered to
import sugar.
</P>
<P>
The over-importation of sugar pulled down the prices of
locally-produced sugar considerably, plunging the country's
downstream sugar industry into a crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
