<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samsung Develops World's First 128 MB Flash Memory Chip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 5 (Xinhua) -- A leading South Korean
electronics giant said Tuesday it has developed the world's first
128 megabytes (MB) flash memory chip.
</P>
<P>
Samsung Electronics Corporation also said it will put the chip
into mass production in July.
</P>
<P>
Smaller than conventional data storage components and often
used in credit card-sized devices, flash memory chips can retain
data even after the power is off and consume less electricity,
said a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The chips are likely to be turned into the next generation of
memory products to replace hard disk drivers in portable computers
and also used in digital camers and other handy digital products.
</P>
<P>
A single 128 MB flash memory chip has the ability to store data
equivalent to those on 1,050 newspaper pages and record up to 30
minutes of voice messages.
</P>
<P>
The worldwide sales of the flash memory chips, 2.6 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, are expected to reach 5 billion dollars by
2000. And Samsung's export could be 250 million dollars by then.
</P>
</TEXT>
