<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Pursues Muslim Extremists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military, backed by
helicopter gunships, continued Thursday its pursuit of a Muslim
extremist group in a remote southern island after a fierce
gunbattle with the rebels Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As of early Thursday morning, skirmishes have been reported
between the pursuing government troops and the extremist Abu
Sayyaf group near Lantawan City in Basilan Province, the
Philippine News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Philippine National Police Provincial Operations Officer
William Manzan confirmed that three extremists were killed while
five soldiers were wounded Wednesday morning in a four-hour
gunbattle.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Army's 103rd Brigade launched this week the
offensive against the Abu Sayyaf, following the killing of at
least 11 fishermen by the extremists last week off the seas of
Lantawan.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, one of the two remaining Muslim rebel groups in
the country, mainly operates in Basilan and its nearby provinces
in southern Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The government, which is engaged in peace negotiations with the
separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), has refused to
open peace talks with the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
The government already signed a peace agreement with the
mainstream Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) in September
1996.  
</P>
