<HEADLINE> Shandong Builds Sewage Plants to Control Water Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province has
planned to invest 1.9 billion yuan into 11 proposed sewage plants
in the coming three years to curb water pollution in the
Huaihe and Haihe river valleys.
</P>
<P>
The province expects to complete the sewage plants, with a
total daily handling capacity of 800,000 cubic meters, by the end
of the century, according to an official from the Shandong
Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 million U.S. dollars in foreign funds have been
earmarked for the projects, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, another 15 sewage plants costing 983 million yuan
(about 12 million U.S. dollars) and dealing with 550,000 cubic
meters of waste water daily will be built in the province before
2010.
</P>
<P>
A total of 95 water disposal centers will be built in the
province by 2010, and they will be able to purify at least 50
percent of its urban drainage, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The heavily polluted Huaihe and Haihe rivers, both winding
through Shandong, do great harm to the people living along the
rivers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has poured 3.2 billion yuan into the
waste water purification efforts since the beginning of the
1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
