<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Incentives Boost China's Agricultural Drive: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Favorable government policies of
fostering farming enthusiasm are the driving force behind China's
agricultural development in the past three decades, said an expert
of the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO).
</P>
<P>
"Providing incentives to the farmers to keep them on the land
and encourage farming activities as a whole is the most successful
aspect of China's agricultural development," said Dr. Samir Miladi
in a recent exclusive interview with Xinhua, shedding his insight
on China's food security program.
</P>
<P>
Miladi, a food policy nutrition officer of FAO's Cairo-based
Near East Office, said his interest in what he called "the Chinese
experience" stemmed from his 27 years of U.N.-affiliated teaching
and research work in around 50 countries.
</P>
<P>
For the past 30 years, China has managed to feed 25 percent of
the world population on 7 percent of the world's cultivated land
while its once malnourished people have grown into a
well-nourished and productive force.
</P>
<P>
Citing a significant barometer to a country's food security
situation, he said the daily energy intake for an average Chinese
rose by 68 percent to 2,757 calories in 1992-94 from 1,638
calories in 1961-63.
</P>
<P>
This, said the expert, can not have been achieved without a
clear government aim to provide food security to all through
offering favorable policies to the peasants.
</P>
<P>
To encourage farming, the Chinese government has provided a
host of incentives to farmers, foremostly, introducing a
production contract system that fixes farm output quotas for each
household while allowing farmers to sell the surplus in free
markets.
</P>
<P>
"This production-pricing-distribution system strikes a good
balance, between the government's task to promote food production
and the farmers' need to make profits," said Miladi.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with a favorable policy was the emphasis on intensive
cultivation and applied technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, health, educational and cultural facilities were
upgraded. Various agro-industry and village business were
encouraged. These measures were designed to keep rural people
where they are.
</P>
<P>
In this aspect, the Chinese experience could well serve as a
good reference to most Arab countries, where urbanization has gone
overboard, said Miladi whose major concern in recent years is in
the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
He said massive rural migration in the Arab world, increasing
at 4-6 percent annually, has not only eroded the quality of urban
life but also crippled the food situation across the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Banks Beef Up Foreign Exchange Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese banks in this largest
economic and financial center of China are beefing up their
efforts to develop foreign exchange business.
</P>
<P>
The domestic banks here had more than 4.99 billion U.S. dollars
in outstanding hard currency deposits by the end of last year, up
11.6 percent over a year ago, according to statistics of the
Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of China (PBC), the central
bank.
</P>
<P>
Early this year Mao Yingliang, governor of PBC Shanghai, urged
Chinese banks to sharpen their competitive edge in foreign
exchange business and achieve new breakthroughs in business of
foreign exchange settlements, letters of credit, and deposits and
loans in foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Shanghai branches of the Bank of China, the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, and Bank of
Communications, are the top three Chinese banks in terms of
foreign exchange business, with their combined hard currency
deposits in excess of 4.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year Chinese banks in Shanghai reversed a trend of decline
in the volume of foreign exchange deposits of enterprises, with
the year-end amount up 13.2 percent year-on-year to 4.18 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that Shanghai's Chinese banks had 8.12
billion U.S. dollars in foreign exchange loans by the end of last
year, up 8.98 percent over a year ago. They accounted for more
than half of the international trade settlements, valued at 17.7
billion U.S. dollars year-round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
