<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Goals for China's Macroeconomic Controls Attainable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Members of China's top legislative
and advisory bodies agreed that macroeconomic control goals set by
the central government for this year are both appropriate and
attainable.
</P>
<P>
However, they acknowledged that there remain some difficulties
in achieving these goals, which could only be overcome by
effective measures of the government.
</P>
<P>
In a government work report he delivered at the opening session
of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) this morning,
Premier Li Peng said China plans to maintain an eight percent
economic growth rate in 1998, while keeping inflation under three
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy grew by 8.8 percent last year, with an
inflation of 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhongli, an NPC deputy from China's largest city
Shanghai, said that since China began to cool down its overheated
economy several years ago, inflation has come down sharply and the
economy has maintained a reasonable and steady annual growth of
eight to nine percent.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that China has basically avoided a bubble economy
and that inflation will remain at a low level this year, providing
a favorable environment for economic development," he predicted.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Ding Xiemin, mayor of Taizhou City in east China's
Jiangsu Province, said that an eight percent economic growth rate
is conducive to achieving a fiscal balance for local governments
and ensuring the employment of urban residents.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Zhuoji, a member of the Ninth National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) which
opened its first annual session Tuesday, said that there are a
host of positive factors for China to maintain a rapid and sound
economic development.
</P>
<P>
These factors include a stable political and social
environment, successive good harvests of crops in recent years, a
sustained influx of foreign investment, and a fairly big amount of
foreign exchange reserves, the economist said.
</P>
<P>
Most NPC deputies and CPPCC members said they endorse central
government macroeconomic control measures as enumerated in the
premier's report, such as an appropriate enlargement of the
investment scale and continued implementation of relatively tight
fiscal and monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
Member of CPPCC Dong Fureng, another noted economist, said
that the Chinese economy is currently at the bottom of its
development cycle.
</P>
<P>
"The government should send correct signals to the market and
encourage an appropriate increase of investment to stimulate
economic growth," he suggested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Foreign Ministers to Meet on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
will meet Monday with his U.S., Russian, French, British and
Italian counterparts to discuss the Kosovo crisis in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the six foreign ministers, Kinkel said Thursday
at the parliament, would take place in London under the framework
of the six-nation contact group for the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the escalation of ethnic violence in
Yugosalvia's autonomous province of Kosovo, Kinkel would also
discuss the Kosovo issue with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright during her brief visit here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We must do everything to prevent an entire region from being
engulfed in flames," the top German diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
should be preserved, Kinkel said, the ethnic Albanian majority in
Kosovo must also have more autonomy.
</P>
<P>
A peaceful solution to the Kosovo conflict holds part of
Serbia's "return ticket" to Europe, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, meanwhile, has held the
position against any foreign intervention on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Tension in Kosovo heightened on March 1 after an escalation of
armed conflict between Serbian police and ethnic Albanians, during
which four policemen and 16 Albanians were killed, and two other
policemen injured.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the population
in Kosovo, have been seeking independence from Yugoslavia since
1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
