<HEADLINE> Getting More Foreign Investment for Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China's Sichuan province has
set its sights on getting more foreign investment in 1998,
according to Li Dachang, the deputy governor, who says that the
key areas are infrastructure, hi-tech industry, tourism
development, upgrading state-owned enterprises, and agricultural
resources.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Sichuan used 880 million US dollars worth of foreign
investment, a significant increase over the previous year. It also
issued H-shares (in Hong Kong) for the Chendu-Chongqing Expressway.
</P>
<P>
To attract more foreign investment, the provincial government
has tried to improve investment conditions and will revise
regulations encouraging foreign investment and formulate more
preferential policies.
</P>
<P>
This year, Sichuan will work out regulations on exploiting
mineral, water, and plant and animal resources.
</P>
<P>
Li says that emphasis will be placed on stopping the arbitrary
charging of fees for foreign-funded enterprises and improving
service and efficiency. 
</P>
