<HEADLINE> Polish Farmers Protest Against EU Agriculture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, March 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 members of Poland's
Rural Solidarity protested Wednesday against plans for the
nation's farming industry after it joins the EU.
</P>
<P>
They held demonstrations in front of the palaces of president
and prime minister, with banners saying "Don't join the EU by
stepping on the backs of farmers", the Polish Press Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The EU is proposing that Poland's farmers go through a 10-year
transition period without EU subsidies while still implementing
the Common Agricultural Policy.
</P>
<P>
But many in the farming industry believe the proposals will
make the country's agricultural products even less competitive,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Polish Deputy Prime Minister and Interior Minister Janusz
Tomaszewski said that some of the measures would disadvantage the
country's farmers. But he stressed that the Polish agricultural
products enjoyed a very good reputation in the western market.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the EU farmers should be more worried
than Poles after his country joined the EU.
</P>
<P>
Poland is expected to formally begin negotiations over its
entry into the EU on March 31.
</P>
<P>
However, Ryszard Czarnecki, chairman of the European
Integration Committee of Polish parliament, said that although
the negotiations would be difficult, Poland "will protect its
economic interests." 
</P>
</TEXT>
