<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Stock Prices Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's stock prices
plunged more than 35 points on Tuesday, the second largest fall
ever.
</P>
<P>
The composite index plunged 37.08 points, or 6.5 percent, to
536.68 due to a flurry of selling by foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Banking, insurance, securities, electric machinery and steel
issues were the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the plunge to political instability caused
by the National Assembly failing to vote on the nomination of
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung Monday appointed Kim
Jong-pil as acting prime minister after a parliamentary vote on
his nomination as prime minister was suspended.
</P>
<P>
The Grand National Party, which has 161 members in the 299-seat
National Assembly, or parliament, vowed to launch a legal and
parliamentary battle to veto the appointment.
</P>
<P>
The largest ever decrease in stock prices was the fall of 38.24
points on November 7, 1997, which saw a serious financial crisis
triggered by corporate failures and bad banking loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
