<HEADLINE> Albania Foreign Minister Urges U.N. on Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal
Milo has urged the U.N. Security Council to monitor the escalating
ethnic conflict in the Yugoslavian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to the Security Council on Wednesday, Milo
asked the U.N. body to express concern over the Kosovo crisis
between ethnic Albanians and the Yugoslavian authorities.
</P>
<P>
The move came as Milo left for talks with the French government
on the Kosovo crisis, said Albanian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Sokol Gjoka.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano had exchanged views on the
Kosovo issue with leaders of some Western European and Balkan
countries by phone.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the population
of Kosovo, have been seeking independence from Yugoslavia since
1981.
</P>
<P>
Tension in Kosovo heightened on March 1 after an escalation of
armed conflict between Serbian police and local ethnic Albanians,
during which four policemen and 16 Albanians were killed, and two
other policemen injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
