<HEADLINE> Women Farmers in Central China Province Learn New Techniques </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The per-hectare cotton output of
Huang Dazhen, a farmer in Honghu village of central China's Hunan
Province, reached 2.63 tons last year, a record high in her village.
</P>
<P>
Huang attributed the high cotton output to the application of
new farming techniques.
</P>
<P>
In the province, about 1.6 million female cotton growers like
Huang have learnt new techniques. As a result, their production
cost has been reduced and cotton output and quality improved.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of female farmers in Hunan have benefited
from various new farming techniques, which were not easy for them
to learn because most of them were illiterate.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the provincial women's federations have helped
350,000 women learn how to read. The province has also organized
500,000 women to learn the techniques of crop growing, animal
breeding and farm produce processing.
</P>
<P>
About 7.2 million women farmers in Hunan have utilized the new
techniques to make financial gains, many of whom now receive a net
annual income of 200,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Yiyang city now has 64,000 family-run enterprises with women as
main workers, 56 pig-raising centers, 95 vegetable production bases,
and 250 farm produce processing plants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
