<HEADLINE> Shakespeare Festival in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A three-day "Shakespeare Festival"
closed here today at the University of International Business and
Economics (UIBE).
</P>
<P>
Students from a dozen local colleges and universities staged
portions from Shakespearean dramas such as "Taming of the Shrew,"
"A Midsummer Night's Dream" and "King Lear."
</P>
<P>
During the festival, British actors from the Royal National
Theater who will perform Shakespeare's "Othello" in Beijing
cooperated with the students in a performance of "Merchant of
Venice."
</P>
<P>
Cheng Feng, a junior at Qinghua University, said his classmates
enjoy Shakespeare's works.
</P>
<P>
"We like most the true-to-life stories about human beings in
his plays," Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the performances, a series of activities were
held such as a photo exhibition, a movie show, a book fair and
contest about the great writer which attracted thousands of
Shakespeare fans nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Su Fuzhong, an expert in publication circles, said that
Shakespeare belongs to the whole world. Chinese readers have
established 295 research associations and reading clubs about
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
Many theater and art troupes in China have staged Shakespearean
dramas in a variety of forms, ranging from plays to Chinese operas.
</P>
<P>
The UIBE festival was sponsored by the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, Central Drama Institute and Chinese People's
Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
