<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Signs Contract with Motorola for Paging Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China's largest public
telecommunications service provider, China Telecom, has signed a
6-million-U.S.-dollar contract with Motorola to expand the 198/199
nationwide multi-frequency roaming paging network.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, China Telecom will purchase Motorola's
state-of-the-art Wireless Messaging System (WMS) for the
second-phase construction of the paging network.
</P>
<P>
Of the nine provincial capitals to be covered by the
second-phase network, six will be supported by the WMS. They are
Taiyuan and Huhhot in north China, Lanzhou, Urumqi and Yinchuan in
northwest China, and Kunming in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Deployment of 198/199's second phase is scheduled to begin in
April this year, according to Jeff Dryjanski, Motorola's
vice-president and general manager of Motorola's Asia-Pacific
Paging Networks.
</P>
<P>
The second-phase network is expected to have an installed
capacity of 1.05 million subscribers, bringing the nationwide
total to 5 million.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of the second phase, which is the last for the
network, the 31 provincial capitals on the mainland will be linked
to form the network's backbone.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom will build upon the backbone to extend network
coverage to all the Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The WMS has been installed to serve eight million subscribers
in 70 Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Motorola is one of the world's leading providers of wireless
communications, semiconductors and advanced electronic systems,
components and services. It recorded 29.8 billion dollars of sales
last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
