<HEADLINE> S. African Security Guards, Employers Hang Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- South African unionized
security guards, whose nationwide strike entered its tenth
consecutive day Wednesday, failed to resolve their dispute with
the employers over pay rise in talks Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two parties would meet in court Thursday, when employers
would appeal against last week's Labor Court ruling that declared
the strike legal, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Security employers and nine unions, which represented about
30,000 striking workers across the country, met Wednesday at the
offices of the Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and
Arbitration, which has been trying to broker a deal between the
two sides since the strike began last Monday.
</P>
<P>
But the parties again failed to agree on terms for ending the
strike, which the employers said had cost the industry millions
of Rand.
</P>
<P>
The major disagreement appeared to be on the guards' demand
for a 17 percent salary increase. The employers are offering a 13
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Court on last Friday dissmissed the application by
the South African Natioanl Securtiy Employers' Association which
asked the strike be declared illegal.
</P>
<P>
Security workers, who started the strike last Monday to demand
higher pay and better working conditions, were still assembled at
the workers' library in Johannesburg Wednesday evening, waiting
for developments in the negotiations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
