<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Trade Union Office Burn After National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The office of the Zimbabwe
Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) in Bulawayo, the country's second
large city was damaged by fire this morning, a day after the
two-day national strike, a ZCTU official said.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU Information Officer Komore Sibanda told Xinhua, "one room
of the office was severely damaged and some furniture, machinery,
documents and fridges were destroyed."
</P>
<P>
He said his office in Bulawayo has reported the police. The
police said they would investigate.
</P>
<P>
Sibanda strongly condemned the destroyed action, adding that
the ZCTU would hold a press conference this afternoon to tell the
fact of the accident.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU organized the countrywide strike Tuesday and
Wednesday to press the government into scrapping a 2.5 percentage
sales tax effected late last year, remove developmental levy,
reduce the prices of all basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
The strike closed most of shops, banks and schools in the
country, causing millions of dollars losses.
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe Monday said his government would not
tolerate violence in activities organized by the ZCTU. "That is
total madness on the part of the ZCTU to go ahead with the
stayaway."
</P>
<P>
Other ministers condemned the strike as illegal.  
</P>
