<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast Asian States Put on "Alert" of Taiwan Authorities' Political Plot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian countries were
urged to properly handle their ties with Taiwan and remain alert
to the political plot of Taiwan authorities by granting economic
aid, according to Zhu Bangzao, spokesman of China's Foreign
Ministry, who spoke here today at a routine news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Zhu's remark came when answering questions on the recent
economic-aid activities by Taiwan authorities among some
crisis-stricken Southeast Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
He said the the stance of the Chinese government on the Taiwan
issue is "clear and consistent." "The Chinese government holds no
disagreement on the non-governmental economic contacts between
relevant countries and Taiwan, but strongly opposes official
contacts in any form by countries which have diplomatic ties with
China," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged countries to respect China's stand in this regard and
to keep their commitment to the "one China" policy in a bid to
safeguard the mutually friendly and cooperative relations for
sound and steady development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government understands the difficulties and context
of certain countries in southeast Asia, he said, adding that China
will not do anything against the interests of those countries.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the Taiwan authorities are "in no position
to provide financial aid in any official form or participate in
any official arrangement in the region."
</P>
<P>
He hoped relevant countries would be in a state of high
alertness on the political plot of the Taiwan authorities aimed at
creating "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan" by using economic
aid.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that "There is only one China in the world. The
government of the People's Republic of China is the sole,
legitimate government representing entire China, and Taiwan is an
inalienable part of China."
</P>
<P>
"Although the territories across the Taiwan Straits have not
yet been reunified, Taiwan's status as part of Chinese territory
remains unchanged and cannot be changed. Chinese sovereignty is
not split and cannot be split," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
