<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Lists Opportunities for Thailand's Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) Thursday listed six priorities or opportunities the
current economic crisis has provided for Thailand for its future
recovery.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Assistant Secretary-General and UNDP Assistant
Administrator Nay Htun, who is also Regional Director for Asia and
the Pacific, said the current financial and economic crisis can
provide a powerful catalyst to institute positive fundamental
changes.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at the opening ceremony of the consultative
meeting of the social impact of the economic crisis and responses
from the government, private sector, civil society and
international community, which was co-sponsored by the UNDP and
the Office of the Prime Minister of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
UNDP suggested that Thailand make efforts to improve
information, to design interventions with short-term and long-term
pay-offs, to restore the environment, to promote social and
investment fund, to promote the sharing of experience and to
increase attention to spill-over effects.
</P>
<P>
He said the with the necessary improvements Thailand will be
back on the road towards economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Htun also hailed the achievements Thailand and Asia have made
during the past two to three decades in human development.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the quality of growth is as important as its
quantity for human development, poverty reduction and long-term
sustainability.
</P>
<P>
"Sustained economic growth and sustained human development can
be mutually reinforcing," he added.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that Thailand's recovery will also be providing
enhanced and sustained benefits to all the people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
