<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Company Exports Smart Cards to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Australian electronics Omnitech
LTD said Thursday it had supplied 200,000 contactless smart cards
to the Shanghai Transit system, and a further 300,000 cards had
been ordered.
</P>
<P>
Omnitech said it would undergo "considerable growth" with its
contactless smart cards and smart card readers, forecasting
exponential returns above 20 million U.S. dollars from a Chinese
contract.
</P>
<P>
The four-year contract, in conjunction with Cubic Corp of the
United States, was worth about 20 million U.S. dollars to Omnitech
when completed, Omintech Chairman Arthur Sturgess was quoted
Thursday by the Australian Associated Press (AAP) as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also said there was potential for additional business using
Omnitech smart card readers on other public transport systems such
as bus and ferry services in China.
</P>
<P>
"If you talk about the expansion of that to bus, ferry and
other transport systems, we are not going to put a figure on it,
but you can see that it's going to grow exponentially," Sturgess
told AAP from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
His chief executive officer, Peter Au, said: "we have discussed
with the appropriate authorities the integration of Omnitech smart
card solutions for the entire Shanghai transport system which
includes rail, bus and ferry."
</P>
<P>
The smart card readers used on the 562-kilometer Shanghai
metro, which services 13 million people, were developed and
designed by Omnitech's subsidiary, VFJ Electronics, in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
In other developments, the second phase of providing
contactless smart cards and small card readers for China's Guangxi
tollway had started, with final implementation expected later this
year, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Discussions with Chinese officials on supplying similar
technology for two other tollways, Chengdu Highway and Guangzhou
Highway, had also commenced, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
VFJ Electronics had also won a contract to supply more than 700
contactless smart card readers and 4,000 cards to Hong Kong Air
Cargo Terminal LTD for the new Chep Lap Kok Airport, opening in
July, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sturgess also said discussions were taking place in Australia
to provide readers for the VISACash system in Sydney, and
Singapore government was considering a fully integrated transport
payments system.
</P>
<P>
"We see opportunities in all of these areas," he said,
referring to a U.S. report forecasting that the smart card
technology business would be valued worldwide at 30 billion U.S.
dollars in 2003 from its present 1 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
