<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Women More Educated Than Men: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli women, aged 25 to 64,
are more educated than men at the same age, according to a latest
survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by Israeli Central Bureau of
Statistics, showed that 51 percent of women in Israel have
completed a high school or higher education, compared to 47
percent of men.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted for the International Women's day which
falls on Sunday, covered Israel's 2.9 million women, who make up a
little bit more than half of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
Israeli women's schooling years went up in the last decade,
reaching an average of 12 years in 1996 as opposed to 10.9 years
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The number of Jewish women who attended college between the
ages of 20 and 29 almost doubled in the past two decades, reaching
11.5 percent in the 1995-96 school year.
</P>
<P>
The survey also said that Israeli women are marrying later than
ever before, and the number of women who do not marry all their
lives has gone up.
</P>
<P>
The average marrying age of Jewish women in Israel was 24.2,
and men got married at an average age of three years older.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, each Jewish woman gave birth to an average of 2.6
children, each Muslim woman in Israel had an average of 4.6 births,
each Christian, 2.6 and Druse, 3.4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
