<HEADLINE> Australian Car Sales Remain Strong in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian vehicle market
remained on track for another record year with a jump in sales of
new cars and trucks in February.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries (FCAI)
said Thursday 62,105 new vehicles were sold last month, an 11.7
percent increase over the 55,605 sold in February last year and up
21.3 percent over the 51,195 retailed in January.
</P>
<P>
The market performance took sales over the first two months to
113,300 units, up 11.8 percent compared to the 101,347 units at
the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
The total sales would jump beyond 800,000 units this year after
reaching a record 722,427 last year if that increase be maintained
over the full 12 months, FCAI said in its car sales bulletin.
</P>
<P>
A strong return to the market by fleet customers and the
continued high levels of competition at the lower end of the
market are generally considered the main reasons for the
improvement so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the ongoing economic problems in various Asian
countries, most Asian car producers have been doing better on the
Australian market so far this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
