<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Cooperation Urged in Fighting Contagious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan health minister Crispus
Kiyonga appealed for a regional cooperation in the Great Lakes
Region to fight contagious diseases, The Monitor reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The health minister said that a coordinated attempt is needed
in utilising limited resources to fight various infectious
diseases including cholera, dysentry, HIC/AIDS, malaria, measles,
meningitis, plague, typhus and vital haemorrhagic fevers such as
ebola.
</P>
<P>
The health minister reminded the health administrators and
experts on contagious diseases from Uganda, Kenya, Tanzania,
Burundi, Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of Congo that more
than 30 highly-infected diseases including sleeping sickness,
tuberculoisis, yellow fever and meningococcal meningitis have
been identified in the region in the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Rampant pandemic of HIV/AIDS should not cover all attention of
regional health administrators and experts, he told the
inauguration ceremony on Tuesday in Kampala.
</P>
<P>
However, Elizabeth Madraa, a delegate from Uganda AIDS control
program, said on the four-day conference that HIV/AIDS is still a
serious threat to the region. He identified refugees, displaced
persons and prostitutes as the sources spreading the disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
