<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Ban Human Cloning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The cloning of human beings
is to be prohibited in South Africa, The Star daily quoted a top
Health Department official as telling parliament Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Director-general of the department, Olive Shisana, said the
new National Health Bill, due to go before cabinet for approval,
would totally outlaw the practice.
</P>
<P>
"We are part and parcel of the world community and the World
Health Organization has taken a decision that, as a general
principle, human cloning is unacceptable. The National Health
Bill is proposing a total ban on human Cloning."
</P>
<P>
The bill, expected to be tabled in parliament before June,
would also outlaw the sale of human organs.
</P>
<P>
Reports that a South African doctor, Mohamed Cassim, attempted
to clone human beings caused a stir in South Africa. But Cassim
later denied the allegations as "bogus."
</P>
<P>
Human cloning became a central issue of debate worldwide after
Scottish scientists cloned a sheep, Dolly, from a cell taken from
the udder of a six-year-old ewe.
</P>
<P>
However, the authenticity of the cloning process is being
questioned by scientists because they failed to repeat the Dolly
experiment.
</P>
<P>
The World Medical Association, an international umbrella of
medical professional groups, has urged doctors and researchers to
abstain voluntarily from participating in the cloning of human
beings until the scientific, ethical and legal issues have been
fully considered.
</P>
<P>
Cloning a human entails removing the nucleus of a human egg
cell and replacing it with the nucleus of a cell from another
part of the body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Steelmakers Develop "Light-weight" Car Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A car body that is 25 percent
lighter than the typical one has been developed, announced
U.S. steel makers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm here to tell you that from now on the words 'lightweight'
and 'steel' can be used in the same sentence," said Robert
J. Damall, chairman of the American Iron and Steel Institute.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Big Three automakers, namely Ford, General Motors and
Chryster, have been researching such lighter vihicles, which can
improve mileage and help reduce emissions vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Some of their high-profile efforts, however, have focused on
car bodies made from aluminum, plastic and fiberglass.
</P>
<P>
The 35 U.S. steel producers, which hold more than 90 percent of
the market for auto bodies, said they want to prove that steel
also can be lightweight.
</P>
<P>
They have spent 22 million U.S. dollars since 1994 to develop
what they call the UltraLight Steel Auto Body.
</P>
<P>
The weight reduction can be achieved at no additional
cost by using higher strength, thinner steel, fewer parts and more
simple frame design and structure, they said.
</P>
<P>
The steel makers urged the Big Three automakers to join them in
designing an even lighter car -- one that would weigh 40 percent
less than midsize cars on the road today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
