<HEADLINE> Egyptian Ambassador: Qatar-Egypt Ties Back to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Relations between Qatar and
Egypt have returned to normal after talks between senior
officials of the two countries, the Egyptian ambassador to Qatar
has said.
</P>
<P>
"Positive signals have emerged from both capitals and now we
can say that the relations are back to normal," local newspaper
Gulf News Thursday quoted Ambassador Mohammed Minessy as saying.
</P>
<P>
Minessy made the remarks after Egyptian Education Minister
Hussein Kamel Bahauddin delivered a letter from Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak to Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa al-Thani
on Tuesday night during a visit to Doha.
</P>
<P>
The letter "which included an invitation for the emir to visit
Egypt" was discussed at the weekly cabinet meeting on Wednesday,
the Qatari official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also discussed a telephone conversation between
Mubarak and the Qatari emir on March 1 "about the good relations
between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Ties between Doha and Cairo soured after a war of words broke
out between them due to Egypt's boycott against the Qatar-hosted
fourth Middle East and North Africa economic conference last
November in protest against Israel's participation.
</P>
<P>
The row was escalated as Qatar's Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad
bin Jassim bin Jabir al-Thani accused Cairo of being behind a
foiled coup attempt in February, 1996 to topple the Qatari
government. Egypt strongly denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
In last January, Mubarak and the Qatari emir held talks in
Riyadh under Saudi Arabia's mediation, but the talks failed to
reach any settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
