<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Says Working Can Help Combat Diabetes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Walking briskly, climbing
stairs, gardening and doing household chores may help prevent
diabetes, according to a study published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our studies showed that, no matter what the activity is,
increased activity is related to improved insulin sensitivity,"
said Elizabeth Mayer-Davis of the University of South Carolina,
lead author of the study.
</P>
<P>
Diabetes occurs when the body is insulin deficient, becomes
impaired in its capacity to use insulin, or both.
</P>
<P>
Researchers analyzed the relationship between insulin
sensitivity -- the body's capacity to use insulin -- and the
exercise among 1,467 men and women aged 40 to 69 in four cities.
</P>
<P>
The study found that even moderate physical activity led to
better insulin sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
Mayer-Davis said the finding is important because people with
diabetes are two to four times more likely to develop heart
disease, and 75 percent of diabetics die of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
She recommended at least 30 minutes of moderate physical
activity everyday, because it "may help the body improve the use
of its own insulin and ward off diabetes". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
weaker Thursday following selling by Japanese investors.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed here at 67.32 U.S. cents, from
67.82 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia treasury manager Paul Macarounas said
selling interest from Japanese investors had capped the Australian
dollar near the 67.50 U.S. cents level.
</P>
<P>
"By the same token there was reasonably good local bank support
down around 67.25 U.S. cents to 67.30 U.S. cents, so it's been a
very tight range today," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said private sector
Average Weekly Ordinary Time Earnings (AWOTE) rose 0.5 percent to
686.40 Australian dollars (461.94 U.S. dollars), in the three
months to November for an annual rate of 3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Public sector AWOTE rose 0.2 percent to 762.60 Australian
dollars (513.22 U.S. dollars), in the same period for an annual
rate of 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
After the release of the data, economists said it was highly
unlikely the Reserve Bank of Australia would raise interest rates,
and that was now a slightly better chance of an easing.
</P>
<P>
A survey of economists by MMS Standard &AMP; Poor's showed the
market considers there is a 17 percent likelihood of a further
rate cut, a four percent chance of a rate hike, and a 79 percent
probability the official cash rate will remain steady at 5.00
percent.
</P>
<P>
HSBC Markets economist Grant Fitzner said wages were not likely
to be a problem for inflation over the coming months, provided
productivity growth remains strong.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rate, the Australian dollar rose to 85.37 from
85.20 against Japanese yen and fell to 1.2216 from 1.2265 against
Deutsche mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
