<HEADLINE> About 2,000 Poachers Arrested in Zambia Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- In an intensified crackdown
against rampant poaching Zambia arrested 1,942 people last year
alone, Times of Zambia reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted tourism minister Amusa Mwanamwambwa
as telling parliament Wednesday that of the 1,942 1,427 have been
convicted in courts of law and a total of 98 million Kwacha
(about 65,000 U.S. dollars) has been paid to the treasury in
court fines.
</P>
<P>
The department of National Parks and Wildlife Service
recovered 253 elephant tusks and confiscated 491 military
weapons, 955 muzzle loading guns, 121 shot-guns and 93 sporting
rifles, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that 22 officers died in the anti-poaching operations
between 1990 and 1997, of which 12 were shot by poachers, eight
killed by wild animals and two drowned.
</P>
<P>
Last year the department collected 1.75 million dollars from
sport hunting by overseas clients and a 403.55 million Kwacha
(about 269,000 dollars) from protein supplementing hunting by
resident hunters, according to him.
</P>
<P>
Investment in the tourism industry continued to grow
appreciably with 10.3 billion Kwacha (about 6.9 million dollars)
pledged to the sector in 1997 with an expected creation of 622
new jobs this year, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
