<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Pulled Lower by BHP Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Fallout from the resignation of
BHP Co LTD chief executive John Prescott impacted on the share
market again Thursday, dragging the local bourse nearly two
percent lower.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished down 52.7 points, or 1.95
percent, at 2652.7, up from an intra-day low of 2646.9.
</P>
<P>
BHP, which Wednesday surged 1.17 to a close of 15.51 Australian
dollars on news of Prescott's resignation, tumbled 51 cents to
finish on volume of 12.5 million as profit-takers moved in.
</P>
<P>
BHP's slide pulled the all resources index back 29.8 points, or
2.56 percent to 1133.7, while the industrials sector plunged 82.7
points for a close of 4555.5.
</P>
<P>
Other resources stocks to suffer included Rio Tinto, which
closed 60 cents cheaper at 19.10. WMC slipped 23 with 7.19 million
shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Among the industrials, News Corp shed 25 cents, while its
preferred shares also gave up 25 cents. Coca-Cola Amatil slumped
47.9 cents, Lend Lease fell 95, Westfield Holdings forfeited 27
and Mayne Nickless shed 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 354.27 million worth 1.165 billion
Australian dollars (784 million U.S. dollars), with falls easily
outpacing rises 811 to 361.
</P>
<P>
The bank index dropped 77.4 points to 5421.7. NAB closed 36
cents lower, CBA shed 30, ANZ slipped 15 while Westpac edged down
only four.
</P>
<P>
The gold index followed the day's trend, slipping 21.4 points
or 1.9 percent to 1095.4, and in Sydney bullion was trading 1.60
weaker at 295.50 U.S. dollars an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
