<HEADLINE> NPC Session Attracts Foreign Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The diplomatic section on the
second floor of the main meeting hall of the Great Hall of the
People was packed this morning with foreign embassy officials
invited to observe the opening session of the Ninth National
People's Congress, China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
"China has made conspicious progresses over the past years.
This congress session will set guidelines for its future
development," said Endymion Wilkinson, head of the resident
European Union Delegation in China, while walking to the meeting
hall. "I wish the session a success."
</P>
<P>
According to officials of the NPC Foreign Affairs Bureau,
attending today's NPC session were a total of 121 foreign
diplomats including 105 ambassadors, a record number for an NPC
session.
</P>
<P>
Brief interviews show that what attract foreign diplomats most
are the new line-up of government leaders, restructuring of the
central government and state enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
Izak V. Human from the South African Embassy said he not only
wanted to know about China's new generation of leaders but is also
interested in how China is going to manage its state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"It's important to manage them well since otherwise there could
be instability," he said.
</P>
<P>
Four New Zealand diplomats, including ambassador Dr. Peter
Adams, came to the session. The ambassador said he was interested
in China's institutional reform.
</P>
<P>
"Such reform has been carried out in New Zealand for the past
15 years. Our goal is to make government smaller and more
efficient. We may learn from each other in this respect," he said.
</P>
<P>
Many embassy officials said they were impressed by Premier Li
Peng's government work report, as it "gives an overall view of
what the government has accomplished in recent years."
</P>
<P>
Thai ambassador Nikhom Tantemsapya expressed appreciation for
China's pledge not to devaluate the Chinese currency. The Chinese
premier's reiteration to maintain the Chinese currency's exchange
rates helps "disperse all doubts, which will in turn contribute to
stabilizing the financial situation" in Southeast Asia, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
