<HEADLINE> Ramos: Political Stability to be Restored in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
expressed confidence here on Thursday that political stability can
be restored soon in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said in a statement that as present chairman of the
standing committee of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN), the Philippines "values highly" the holding of free
elections and the restoration of political stability in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the forthcoming meeting between the ASEAN
Troika (Indonesia, the Philippines and Thailand) and the 'Friends
of Cambodia' will substantially contribute to the attainment of
these goals," he said.
</P>
<P>
The "Friends of Cambodia" is an informal group whose members
come from the United States, Russia and some European Union
countries. The group held a meeting with the ASEAN Troika last
month in Manila to discuss providing aid to Cambodian elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Foreign Affair Secretary Domingo Siazon reported to
Ramos that the two groups would meet again in Manila on Friday to
discuss the preparations being made for the Cambodian elections on
July 26.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said he has taken note of the recent developments in
Cambodia during the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"It is encouraging to hear recent pronouncements from His
Excellency Hun Sen (second prime minister) on Cambodia's
continuing desire to join ASEAN," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramos welcomed the decision of Cambodian King
Norodom Sihanouk to return to his country next month, saying the
King "plays a very important rule in unifying the Cambodian people
and in reinforcing institutional arrangements in that country."
</P>
<P>
Other ASEAN members are Brunei, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
Singapore and Vietnam. Cambodia was denied admission to the
regional group last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
