<HEADLINE> UN Chief to Visit Egypt on March 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan is due here on March 18 for his first visit to Egypt
since taking the job as chief of the world organization, the
Egyptian Gazette reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Annan's visit to Egypt will be part of a multi-leg Mideast
tour, which will also take him to Syria, Lebanon, Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule areas, the English daily quoted diplomatic
sources here as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Annan will discuss with leaders of these
countries a host of regional issues, including means to revive the
Middle East peace process and boosting cooperation between the
world body and these countries.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe, Annan, with a deal at hand to ease the
Iraqi-U.N. crisis over arms inspection, will confer with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on the peacemaking in the Middle East and
the implementation of the U.N resolutions on the decades-old
Arab-Israeli conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Annan is also expected to hold talks with Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa on the latest regional and international
developments and envisaged U.N. reform.
</P>
<P>
Annan, a Ghanan, who had been working with the world body for
30 years, is the first U.N. chief to assume the office from inside.
</P>
<P>
On New Year's Day in 1997, Annan, U.N. undersecretary-general
at that time, replaced former Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, an Egyptian who retired at the end of his five-year
term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
