<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Warned Against Dumping Bad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official has
warned foreign investors coming to Zambia against turning the
country into a dumping ground for sub-standard goods, Times of
Zambia reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This warning was issued in Lusaka Wednesday by Ackim Nkole,
Deputy Minister of Commerce, Trade and Industry, when he
officiated at the launching of a kind of biscuits on the local
market.
</P>
<P>
Nkole said that investors are free to export and import goods
but reiterated the government's call on investors not to use
Zambia as a dumping ground for sub-standard goods.
</P>
<P>
Nkole told foreign investors to ensure the imports they
brought in are of high quality and not harmful to the health of
the people, adding that "the imports should be environment
friendly."
</P>
<P>
In a response to a large number of second-hand refrigerators
imported from abroad, investors should ensure imported goods such
as refrigerators are friendly to the environment and does not
emit toxic gases.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia is not going to be used as a transmission ground for
scrap metal," said the deputy minister.
</P>
<P>
He stated that foreign investors should be mindful about the
life-span of foodstuffs on the shelves or the Zambian government
will confiscate and destroy them.
</P>
<P>
The government is seriously concerned with the manufacturing
and expiry dates on imported goods especially foodstuffs, Nkole
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
