<HEADLINE> U.N. Agencies Help Zimbabwe's Land Policy Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) and the Food and Agricultural Organisation (FAO)
Wednesday signed a 195,000 U.S. Dollar agreement to help the
country in mapping out a new land policy.
</P>
<P>
The money is designed to carry out a study project for
Zimbabwe with the Ministry of Lands and Agriculture, according to
a report from the Zimbabwean News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Zimbabwe's Lands and
Agriculture Minister Kumbirai Kangai said his ministry had a long
and fruitful collaboration with the two U.N. organizations which
had jointly funded the study.
</P>
<P>
He said the national land policy would look at evaluating the
existing administrative and institutional arrangements for land
administration, review the current farm or agricultural land
sub-division policy and recommend the most appropriate criteria
among others.
</P>
<P>
"To this end an international expert and four local experts in
the land policy and land reform have been commissioned jointly by
FAO and the Zimbabwean government to carry out this national land
policy project," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same occasion, UNDP Resident Representative
Carlos Lopes said as part of the 1997/2000 country cooperation
framework for Zimbabwe, the UNDP agreed with the Zimbabwean
government to support areas of critical importance to the nation
especially those that resolve poverty alleviation. 
