<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Level of Yangtze River Low in Upper Reaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The water in the upper reaches of
the Yangtze River has been at its lowest level in the past 36
years, while the middle and lower reaches have had record high
run-off levels.
</P>
<P>
Jin Xingping, of the Yangtze River Hydrological Bureau, says
that, in February, the water level of the Jialing River, a major
tributary of the Yangtze, was at its lowest since 1952 and that
the average flow on the upper reaches of the Yangtze was 30 percent
less than the average for the same period in recent years. He
attributes this to drought and decreased rainfall in the valleys
along the upper Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that increased rainfall and run-off along
the middle and lower reaches have something to do with El
Nino. Normally, he explained, rainfall will increase on the middle
and lower reaches of the Yangtze in the year after El Nino
occurs. However, rainfall and surface run-off on the upper reaches
do not have any clear relation with El Nino.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee shipping on the upper reaches, departments in
charge of shipping have started dredging there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
