<HEADLINE> China to Sell 700,000 Personal Computers for Home Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Some 700,000 Chinese families are
expected to buy personal computers this year, according to experts
with the Ministry of Electronics Industry.
</P>
<P>
The figure will account for about 17 percent of sales of personal
computers in China this year, one expert said.
</P>
<P>
There has seen a rapid market growth for home-use computers in
the past few years. Statistics show that 61 percent of PC's
nationwide were bought in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The country sold 220,000 home-use computers in 1995, 340,000 in
1996, and 540,000 in 1997, rising over 50 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
However, Chinese families own fewer computers than those in
developed countries because of late development in the country's
computer industry.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing and Shanghai, only six out of one hundred families
own personal computers, compared with 20 in Japan and 38 in the
United States. Endtiem

