<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BJP's Prospects to Form India's Govt. Brighten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bharatiya Janata Party
(BJT), India's largest political force, has moved closer towards
formation of a new government at the center as efforts by its
opponents to forge a secular alliance have gone rough.
</P>
<P>
BJP claimed Wednesday that it had already secured a "working
majority" of 260 MPs to stake its claim to form a new government
and its target was to obtain an absolute majority of 272 seats or
above in the newly-elected Lok Sabha, the lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Party General Secretary Pramod Mahajan said BJP and its allies
had already obtained the support from half a dozen independents.
</P>
<P>
The BJP and its allies have secured 255 out of the 535
contested seats in the first three phases of the four-phased
elections to the Lok Sabha, which means it at least needs another
21 seats for a clear majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
BJP's opponent, the congress and its allies won 167 seats while
the United Front got 93.
</P>
<P>
The Congress and the United Front have so far still been
divided on whether they should come together to form the next
government while the left parties threw the ball into the
Congress' court, indicating that the United Front should take a
stand after it made up its mind on the formation of a non-BJP
government.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that the United Front would take a final
decision Thursday on its stand on government formation.  
</P>
