<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands Supports Anti-pollution Project In Huaihe Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands will provide
grants of nearly three million U.S. dollars to support China's
anti-pollution efforts in the Huaihe River Valley, according to an
official with the National Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
The fund, offered by the Netherlands' Ministry of Economic
Affairs, will mainly pay for a preparatory project for the World
Banks's anti-pollution project in the Huaihe River Valley. The
World Bank has provided China with 400 million dollars in loans to
combat pollution in the valley.
</P>
<P>
The preparatory project, beginning this year for two years,
will cover the draft of an overall plan for pollution control in
the valley, the establishment of mathematical models and control
of urban sewage and industrial pollution.
</P>
<P>
The Huaihe River, the country's most seriously polluted river,
flows across Henan, Anhui, Shandong and Jiangsu provinces. The
government has closed several thousand heavy-polluting factories
such as paper mills and tanneries in the valley.
</P>
<P>
After several years, all the factories in the valley meet the
state's pollution emission standards. China plans to declare the
river clean by the end of this century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
