<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Inflation Rate Goes Up in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' inflation rate
went up to 7.4 percent in February from 6.4 percent last month,
due to price increase of nearly all commodities, the National
Statistics Office (NSO) said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On a year-on-year basis, all the commodity groups recorded
higher inflation rates except for that of housing and repairs, the
NSO said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
It added that food, fuel, light and water are among the
commodities posting highest inflation rates.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review, the inflation rate for Metro
Manila rose to 8.4 percent from 7.8 percent last month while areas
outside the capital posted a rate of 7.1 percent from 6.0 percent
last month, the NSO said.
</P>
<P>
Economists, who attributed the upsurge of inflation to the
current currency crisis, noticed that the inflation rate in
February was 2.3 percentage points higher than the averaged 5.1
percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
