<HEADLINE> NZ Primary School Teachers Win Equal Pay Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Over 20,000 New Zealand primary
school teachers are now on the verge of winning their battle for
equal pay with their secondary school colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The teachers have all but signed an agreement to get the pay,
the Wellington newspaper The Evening Post reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Education Minister Wyatt Creech as saying that "the
agreement between the Government and the primary teachers' union
over the final shape of the unified pay system for teachers is a
historic achievement.
</P>
<P>
Creech said the settlement honored the promise to pursue the
system "with vigor" as embodied in the agreement to form the
coalition government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The deal will come after seven months of negotiations and four
years of effort by the teachers, including two national strikes.
</P>
<P>
The primary school teachers, assistant principals and deputy
principals can now look forward to their pay rises backdated to
the start of February. The report said the pay rises average 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
The deal has also opened the opportunity for a unified union
for both primary and secondary school teachers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
