<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Fifth Five-Year Plan Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi National Economic
Council (NEC) has approved the country's Fifth Five-Year Plan
(1997-2002), aimed at poverty alleviation, achieving self-reliance
in food and creating jobs, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which was approved at an NEC meeting on Wednesday,
would involve 1,959.52 billion taka (about 42.6 billion U.S.
dollars), with 56 percent to be invested in the private sector and
the remaining 44 percent in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-eight percent of the total investment would come from
local resources, with the rest from foreign assistance and direct
foreign investment, State Minister for Planning Mohiuddin Khan
Alamgir was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plan envisaged a 23 percent growth in investment in the
power and gas sector by the 2001-02 fiscal year, 14 percent in the
industrial sector, 7.7 percent in construction, and 4 percent in
agriculture, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The growth of investment in education would stand at 6.5
percent, in the health sector 6.3 percent, in commerce 7.9 percent
and in transport, 7.5 percent, according to the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
