<HEADLINE> Flood Death Toll Reaches 100 in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Death toll in flash floods that
swept away hundreds of mud homes in Turbat, southwestern Pakistan,
has reached over 100 while another 1,200 people were missing and
many of them were feared dead.
</P>
<P>
A large-scale joint rescue operation has been launched by the
army, navy, coastal guards and civilian staff in the areas around
Turbat, headquarters of Makran Division in southwestern
Balochistan province, which was severely hit by devastating flood
following 36-hour torrential rains on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a handout issued by the Balochistan provincial
government, an estimate of 3,000 houses in the division have been
completely washed away while the flood caused damages to another
6,000 houses.
</P>
<P>
The Federal government has dispatched relief goods through a
special aircraft, and the provincial Balochistan government
announced 6 million rupees (about 130,000 U.S dollars) for the
relief of flood-hit people of Makran Division.
</P>
<P>
Balochistan Chief Minister Sardar Akhtar Mengal Wednesday
visited the flood-affected area and distributed checks to the
local people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
