<HEADLINE> Albright for More Constructive Ties With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here Wednesday that her country is for a
more constructive relationship with China in spite of differences
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Testifying before the House Appropriations Committee on foreign
operations, she said that the United States is working to promote
stability in Asia at a time of uncertainty by solidifying links
with its allies in the region, while seeking concrete steps to
better ties with China.
</P>
<P>
"We also seek to build a more constructive relationship with
China through concrete steps and through our strategic dialogue,"
the secretary told the lawmakers, who are debating over the
budgetary allocations for foreign operations in the financial year
1998.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that China is moving in the right direction,
citing as evidence its commitment to strictly control nuclear
exports and its security cooperation on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
She also spoke highly of China's continued economic reforms,
its positive role in responding to the East Asian economic crisis,
its invitation to the U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights to
visit and its efforts to strengthen the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Albright defended the government's decision to start peaceful
nuclear cooperation with China, saying that China has acted
consistently with its pledge not to assist unsafeguarded nuclear
facilities in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton certified to Congress last month that
China has strictly controlled nuclear exports, in an effort to get
the congressional approval to carry out the long-delayed agreement
on peaceful nuclear cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that China is serious about this commitment," the
secretary replied to skepticism expressed by some House
representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
