<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Plebiscite on Puerto Rico's Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives narrowly approved a bill on Wednesday that would
grant Puerto Rico political self-determination for the first time
since it becomes a U.S. possession a century ago.
</P>
<P>
The House passed the bill by just 209-208, which still needs to
be approved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The bill, sponsored by Alaska Republican Don Young, allows the
Caribbean island to hold a plebiscite by the end of the year on
whether it becomes a U.S. state, breaks away as an independent
nation or remains a U.S territory.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, strongly backed by the Clinton administration,
if a majority of Puerto Ricans vote for statehood or for
independence, the president must submit to Congress a plan for a
10-year transition.
</P>
<P>
"This is a bill that establishes the right of Puerto Rico to
self-determination for the first time in 100 years," said Young.
</P>
<P>
"The 3.8 million citizens in Puerto Rico have waited an entire
century for the United States to provide them with this
opportunity," Young told a news conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
New York Republican Gerald Solomon proposed making English the
only official language in Puerto Rico if it becomes a state, and
requiring Puerto Rican public schools to teach in English.
</P>
<P>
The effort was rejected earlier in the day. The House also
rejected an effort by Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., to allow Puerto
Ricans now living in the 50 states to vote in the special
referendum.
</P>
<P>
The United States took over the former Spanish colony after the
1898 Spanish-American War. Its citizens has no right to vote in
the U.S. elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
