<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Calls for Peaceful End to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Albania called for a peaceful
solution to the escalating ethnic conflict in Kosovo, an
Albanian-dominated province of the Yugoslav Republic of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Foreign Ministry spokesman Sokol Gjoka told a press
conference here Wednesday that Albania advocates a direct dialogue
between Yugoslav authorities and leaders of the Kosovo
Albanians. The dialogue should also be attended by representatives
from international organizations, Gjoka added.
</P>
<P>
Such a dialogue will help prevent the escalation of the crisis
and the possible evacuation of Albanians from Kosovo, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo was an autonomous province that formed part of Serbia
until 1989 when Serbian authorities unilaterally revoked the
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo has a 90 percent ethnic Albanian majority that has been
seeking independence from Yugoslavia since 1981. Violence there
has been growing this year following the non-implementation of an
education agreement reached between Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and the leader of ethnic Albanians, Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<P>
Referring to activities made by some political forces in
Albania to support the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, Gjoka noted
that the Albanian government opposes any attempts that will lead
to the escalation of the Kosovo dispute.
</P>
<P>
On international efforts to help end the crisis, the spokesman
said Albania should play a more active role in the mediation. But
so far the Albanian government has not yet contacted the Yugoslav
authorities on the issue, he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. envoy to Bosnia Robert Gelbard however said on Wednesday
that the United States might consider a military intervention in
the Kosovo crisis. Since 1989, the Bush administration and the
Clinton administration have threatened to intervene if Yugoslavia
attempts to solve the Kosovo crisis by force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Birth Rate in Italy for Fourth Straight Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Italy saw a reduced birth rate in
the native population for the fourth straight year in 1996,
Italian Central Institute of statistics (CIS) said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A 1996 report on population statistics from CIS said there was
a drop of 21,000 in the number of births of native Italians from
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
But the total population in Italy increased in 1996 over the
previous year to a total of 57.4 million due to the influx of
foreigners, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the floating population, a phenomenon
rarely observed before in Italy, was remarkable in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.2 million people relocated, mostly from large
cities to small towns, to take advantage of more comfortable
living conditions and a less polluted environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
