<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland Ready to Declassify Dirty Money Deposits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland is prepared to
investigate secret bank accounts opened by Bulgarians for illegal
earnings in an attempt to help Sofia regain stolen funds.
</P>
<P>
The declassification of accounts just depends on Sofia making
an official request, Swiss State Secretary for Foreign Economic
Affairs Franz Blankart said during a visit to Bulgaria on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland had no intention of keeping bank accounts holding
illegal earnings confidential, Blankart told Nadezhda Mihailova,
Bulgaria's foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Blankart's remarks gave Sofia hope that at least some of the
money that has been illegally transferred out of the country could
be recovered, said Radko Vlaikov, spokesman of the Bulgarian
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Blankart said at talks with Bulgarian Trade Minister Valentin
Vassilev that his visit is the first of a series of meetings
preparing for the annual conference of the World Trade
Organization (WTO). The aim of the conference in Geneva in late
April is to prepare for WTO expansion.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria and Switzerland are expanding cooperation in trade and
tourism. Switzerland has been training Bulgarian entrepreneurs and
specialists in export insurance, and funding a water treatment
facility in Plovdiv, Bulgaria's second largest city. Large Swiss
companies, such as ABB and Elektrowaz, are joint partners in
restructuring Bulgaria's hydro-electric plants.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also set up an eco-fund under a
debt-for-environment program. In 1995, the Swiss government wrote
off about 20 million Swiss francs of Bulgarian debt. Sofia pledged
to invest the money in environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
Blankart will also hold talks with Bulgarian President Peter
Stoyanov, Prime Minister Ivan Kostov and other senior officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Consumer Market Growing Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese consumer market has
enjoyed stable growth for the last five years, with the sales
rising 180 percent from 1992 to 2.48 trillion yuan last year,
according to a report by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
With inflation taken into consideration, the Chinese consumer
market grew at an annual rate of 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the 1993-1997 period was characterized by
a buyers' market, with a survey showing that only 10 types of
commodities out of 613 had a shortage of supply in the second half
of last year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the appearance of a buyers' market
promotes the structural readjustment of the national economy as
well as reform in production and distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the abundant supply of commodities to a
sustained industrial growth and good harvests.
</P>
<P>
During the past five years China completely lifted its
control over prices of industrial products as well as prices of
grain, edible oil and other farm products.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the state controls prices for less than 5 percent of
commodities.
</P>
<P>
The report added that the rural market and the urban market
enjoyed the roughly same prosperity during the last five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Car Exports Up By 40 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Auto exports of the Czech Republic
earned about 2.68 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, an increase of
63.3 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Czech State Statistics Bureau said Wednesday that the auto
industry of the country grew by up to 40 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The production and sales of Skoda cars, a famous make which was
sold in more than 70 countries and regions, amounted to 357,000
and 336,000 units respectively in 1997 and the previous year,
breaking a record.
</P>
<P>
The auto industry has become the country's pillar industry,
making up 10.6 percent of the total industry and 12.4 percent of
the total exports from the Czech Republic. 
</P>
