<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on International Situation and Diplomatic Work (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Faced with a new international
situation, China will as always uphold its independent foreign
policy of peace and open up new vistas in diplomatic work, said Li
Peng today.
</P>
<P>
In his last government work report as premier of the State
Council, Li recalled China's fruitful diplomatic activities over
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the First Session of the Ninth National People's
Congress (NPC) today, Li pointed out that China's friendly
relations and cooperation with other countries and regions have
steadily improved, securing a favorable external environment for
its reform program, open policy implementation and modernization
drive.
</P>
<P>
In diplomatic work, he said, China has safeguarded its
sovereignty, territorial integrity and national dignity by
adhering to principles and resisting pressure.
</P>
<P>
China's solidarity and cooperation with developing countries
has further strengthened and its relations with developed
countries have improved. China's international standing has kept
going up, he said.
</P>
<P>
Peace and development remain the two main themes of the world
today, Li said. The international situation is undergoing major
and profound changes. Big powers continue to readjust their
relations. The overall strength of developing countries as a whole
is increasing. The trend towards multipolarity is becoming
increasingly clear.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that international economic links have become tighter
and tighter, and science and technology are advancing by leaps and
bounds, both of which are exerting a major influence on world
political, economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Sino-US relations, Li Peng said President Jiang
Zemin made a successful state visit to the United States last
year, which has ushered Sino-US relations into a new stage of
development.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the two sides can work together to seek common
ground while putting aside differences and increase cooperation on
the basis of the three Sino-US joint communiques and the Sino-US
Joint Statement so as to promote new substantial developments in
our bilateral relations," Li said.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-Russian relations, he said China and Russia signed
Joint Statement by the People's Republic of China and the Russian
Federation on global multipolarization and the establishment of a
new international order and completed demarcation work for the
eastern section of their border in accordance with relevant
agreements.
</P>
<P>
"We should further expand cooperation and exchanges between the
two countries in such fields as economy, trade, science and
technology and step up mutual consultation and cooperation on
international issues," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on International Situation and Diplomatic Work (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Development in Sino-Japanese relations has on the whole
maintained a good progressive momentum, he said. "We support Japan
in taking the road to development through peace. We maintain that
it is necessary to draw lessons from history, set our eyes on the
future and properly handle existing problems and disagreements so
as to make fresh improvements in the friendly relationship and
good-neighborly cooperation between the two countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
China is ready to develop stable, long-term, mutually
beneficial cooperative relations with the European Union and other
European countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will further develop its friendly and good-neighborly
relations with the countries bordering China. The country will
establish a long-term partnership of good-neighborliness and
mutual trust with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
"We will maintain our friendly relations with the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea, promote mutually beneficial
cooperation with the Republic of Korea and strive to maintain
peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula," he said.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to develop its friendly relations and
cooperation with countries in South and Central Asia. China will
strengthen its solidarity and cooperation with the vast number of
developing countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
China will enhance mutual consultation and render mutual
support in regional and international affairs so as to jointly
safeguard the rightful interests of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The country will explore new ways of economic cooperation and
develop new types of economic relations and trade of mutual
benefit and reciprocity, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said China will continue to play a constructive role in the
affairs of the United Nations. China will actively participate in
the activities of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation and the
Asia-Europe Meeting and take part in other multilateral diplomatic
activities of a global, intercontinental and regional nature.
</P>
<P>
Li pointed out that China has all along attached importance to
the issue of human rights and has acceded to 17 international
covenants on human rights.
</P>
<P>
He noted China has already signed the International Covenant on
Economic, Social and Cultural Rights of the United Nations and is
now deliberating on accession to the International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
"It is China's position to conduct dialogue with various
parties on the basis of equality and mutual respect, but we are
firmly opposed to any attempt to interfere in a country's internal
affairs under the pretext of human rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has all along maintained that
state-to-state relations should be established on the basis of the
Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence and that disputes should
be settled peacefully through consultations on an equal footing.
Resolutely opposed to hegemonism in whatever form, China is
forever an important force contributing to world peace and
regional stability, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on International Situation and Diplomatic Work (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese government maintains that relations between
countries should be based on the Five Principles of Peaceful
Co-existence and that all disputes should be settled peacefully
through equal consultations instead of resorting to the use of
force or military threats, he said.
</P>
<P>
China highly appreciates mediation efforts made by UN
secretary-general Kofi Annan for the peaceful solution of the
Iraqi weapons inspection crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China holds that the memorandum of understanding reached
between UN secretary-general Kofi Annan and the Iraqi government
should be carried out to the letter," he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that China resolutely opposes hegemonism of
any form and will serve permanently as an important force in
maintaining world peace and regional stability.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government and people are ready to work with all
other governments and peoples of the world to make their due
contribution to establishing a peaceful, stable, just and
equitable new international political and economic order and to
promoting the lofty cause of world peace and development," he
concluded. 
</P>
