<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Problems in Economic and Social Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, premier of the State
Council, acknowledged today that there are shortcomings and defects
in the work of the government and the Chinese government is fully
aware that there are still quite a few conflicts and problems in
the country's economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report at the First Session of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC), Li said his government has tried
to solve these problems in recent years, but the result is far
from satisfactory and some problems have become even more serious.
</P>
<P>
"It remains an arduous task for the government to continue
tackling these conflicts and problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
The main problems he cited include the following:
</P>
<P>
-- Quite a number of state-owned enterprises are experiencing
difficulties in production and operation, causing an increase in
unemployment and resulting pressures;
</P>
<P>
-- China's agriculture as the foundation of the economy is
still fragile;
</P>
<P>
-- There is blindness in investment with many redundant
construction projects and the quality and performance of the
national economy as a whole remain poor;
</P>
<P>
-- The supervision and control over finance is imperfect and
the financial order in some areas is somewhat chaotic;
</P>
<P>
-- Uneven regional development is obvious. The distribution of
income needs to be straightened out. A portion of both urban and
rural residents still live under difficult circumstances;
</P>
<P>
-- Current social conduct and public security still short of
the expectations of the people. Bureaucratic behavior divorced
from the needs of the masses and proneness to boasting and
exaggeration divorced from reality are serious problems among some
government functionaries, and corruption, extravagance and waste
are still spreading and growing.
</P>
<P>
-- Population growth and economic development have caused a
great strain on resources and the natural environment continues to
deteriorate in some areas. Some of these problems were left over
from the past and others have emerged in the course of reform and
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Calls for Making New breakthroughs in Reform of State Firms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng called for
working hard to achieve new breakthroughs in reform of state-owned
enterprises in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Li made the call in his government work report he delivered at
the First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC)
this morning. He devoted about one tenth of his report to
discussing reform of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Reform of state-owned enterprises is the principal task of the
on-going economic restructuring," he said.
</P>
<P>
China's decision-makers announced last year that through
reform, reorganization, upgrading and improved management, China
will have extricated most large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises operating at a loss from their predicament within
about three years.
</P>
<P>
Li reaffirmed that China will strive to establish
initially a modern enterprise system in the majority of large and
medium-sized state-owned key enterprises by the end of the
century.
</P>
<P>
Guiding ideas and basic tasks for reform of state-owned
enterprises listed by Li Peng are as follows:
</P>
<P>
--Taking reform of state-owned enterprises as the central point
in economic restructuring, China will change the way enterprises
operate, with the establishment of a modern enterprise system as
its orientation.
</P>
<P>
--Guiding enterprises according to their type and aiming at
improving the state sector of the economy as a whole, the Chinese
government will carry out a strategic reorganization of
state-owned enterprises by learning to manage large enterprises
well while relaxing control over small ones.
</P>
<P>
--Exploring various forms for realizing public ownership.
</P>
<P>
-- The central government will combine its efforts to reform
state enterprises with efforts to reorganize, upgrade and exercise
more effective management of them.
</P>
<P>
-- Encouraging mergers, standardizing bankruptcy procedures,
redirecting laid-off workers, increasing efficiency by reducing staff
and implementing re-employment programs.
</P>
<P>
-- Promoting supportive reforms which focus on the
establishment of a social security system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Calls for Making New Breakthroughs in Reform of State Firms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Measures Li Peng proposed in his government work report
include:
</P>
<P>
--Pressing ahead with reform and development of key industries
and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Beginning with the textile industry, the government will
encourage industries in difficulty to deepen reform, turn their
losses into profits and surmount financial problems.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of preliminary successes in this field, the
central government will spread similar practices to the ordnance,
machinery and other difficulty-ridden industries.
</P>
<P>
In important industries and key fields, the government will
encourage the establishment of large enterprise groups in order to
increase their competitiveness in both domestic and foreign
markets.
</P>
<P>
In the promotion of enterprise groups, market orientation will
be emphasized. Efforts will be made to break departmental,
regional and ownership barriers, support association between
strong enterprises so that they can take advantage of each other's
strength and thereby prevent the practice of simply piecing
together groups and indiscriminately expanding the scale of
operations.
</P>
<P>
The State Council should strengthen financial supervision in
large state-owned enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
--Accelerating the reorganization and readjustment of
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The government will encourage strong enterprises to merge with
difficulty-ridden ones so as to use resources efficiently. The
government will, in accordance with relevant regulations, declare
bankrupt enterprises which have been operating at a loss for a
long period of time and have no hope of ending such a situation.
</P>
<P>
"We should be resolute in shutting down a number of enterprises
whose products are unmarketable and whose survival is difficult,"
Li said.
</P>
<P>
Redirecting surplus employees of enterprises is an important
way of raising efficiency, and governments at all levels should
support this endeavor, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Calls for Making New breakthroughs in Reform of State Firms (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We shall continue to implement, in selected experimental
cities and key industries, preferential policies that support
enterprises when they carry out mergers and bankruptcies and try
to increase efficiency through reducing staff size," he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, he said, total capital reserves earmarked for clearing
the bad debts of banks should be raised to 40 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In this endeavor, he said, the government will prevent concealed
avoidance of debt payment so as to protect the security of
bank assets. Both central and local governments should take
measures to reduce the burden of debt on enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The government will continue to alleviate enterprises' debt
burdens by turning loans and capital construction operational
funds into state capital in relevant enterprises. The government
will turn 50 billion yuan of such debts into state capital this
year.
</P>
<P>
--Actively and steadily carrying out reform involving the joint
share system and the joint stock cooperative system.
</P>
<P>
The government will corporatize large and medium-sized
enterprises in a standard way where conditions permit, allowing
some enterprises to be listed and issue stocks in accordance with
market conditions.
</P>
<P>
In enterprise reform, efforts should be made to delineate the
rights and responsibilities of the state and the enterprise,
improve the enterprise's internal management system, and prevent
the devaluation of state assets, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng called for relaxing controls over small state-owned
enterprises and invigorating them by way of reorganization,
association, merger, leasing, contract operation, the joint stock
cooperative system and sell-off.
</P>
<P>
"We should make sure that the right to independent operation is
delegated to small enterprises so that they can practice
democratic management, be responsible for their own profits and
losses and adapt themselves to the market in a more flexible way.
We must choose suitable means of reform in light of differing
conditions and refrain from seeking speedy results
indiscriminately," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Calls for Making New breakthroughs in Reform of State Firms (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
--Improving the leadership, operation and management of
enterprises. Methods of selecting, supervising, examining,
rewarding and punishing managers should be improved.
</P>
<P>
Personnel of enterprises should change their thinking so that
production, operation and internal management can meet the needs
of the market, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must attach importance to speeding up technological
progress, developing new products, readjusting the product mix,
improving marketing and after-sale services, striving to reduce
costs, raise quality and become more competitive," Li Peng said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier urged governments at all levels to actively
help enterprises divest themselves of social functions.
</P>
<P>
--Pressing ahead with all other reforms. "We should continue to
readjust and improve the pattern of ownership," he said.
</P>
<P>
While promoting reform and development of the state sector of
the economy, the central government will actively develop various
forms of collective economy in urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The government will encourage and guide individual, private and
other non-public sectors of the economy to grow simultaneously.
Efforts will be made to quicken reform of the social security
system including workers' basic old-age insurance, medical
insurance and unemployment insurance, so as to pave the way for
reform of state-owned enterprises and readjustment of the economic
structure.
</P>
<P>
In the field of distribution, it is necessary to break regional
blockades and trade monopolies, rectify order in the market and
crack down on such illegal acts as producing and distributing fake
or shoddy goods, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said China will press ahead with the agent system.
Association between large production enterprises and distribution
firms and between domestic and foreign trade businesses will be
encouraged so that they will jointly develop markets at home and
abroad, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
