<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Assisting laid-off workers to find
new jobs and guaranteeing their basic needs is a pressing task for
the government in 1998, Chinese Premier Li Peng said here today.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report he delivered at the First Session
of the Ninth National People's Congress, Li said that in the
process of reforming state-owned enterprises and readjusting the
economic structure, there will be some layoffs, which will cause
temporary hardships and put more pressure on employment.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he said, "The potential for employment is great
and, so long as we handle this challenge well, we shall be able to
create more job opportunities."
</P>
<P>
The number of layoffs has increased year by year since the end
of the 1980s. The figure rose to more than 10 million by the end
of last year.
</P>
<P>
"We should rely on all quarters of the society to provide
better employment services and vocational training for
re-employment. We should also support laid-off workers in seeking
new jobs on their own and encourage them to become self-employed
or to work in the private sectors of the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
They should be encouraged to engage in and expand badly-needed
community services, property management and household services.
This will involve less investment and quicker results, he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier called for guaranteeing the basic needs of laid-off
workers and show concern for employees in enterprises experiencing
difficulties and also for retired employees who are struggling
financially.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China should accelerate the establishment of a
minimum standard of living for impoverished urban residents, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Restructure Government Institutions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's highest
governing body, has drafted a restructuring program which calls
for the 40 existing ministries and commissions of the State
Council to be reduced to 29, According to Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
Li unveiled the program in his government work report he delivered
at the First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC)
today.
</P>
<P>
China has undergone restructuring of government institutions on
three occasions since the end of 1979, respectively in 1982, 1988
and 1993, which have produced positive results, he said. However,
the incompatibilities of government institutions with the
development of a socialist market economy have become increasingly
apparent.
</P>
<P>
Unwieldy organization and failure to separate the functions of
the government from those of the enterprise have given rise to
bureaucracy, bred unhealthy practices and created a heavy
financial burden, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li noted restructuring government institutions is urgently
needed to deepen economic restructuring and promote economic
and social development.
</P>
<P>
"It constitutes an important aspect of reform of the system of
leadership of the state and is also a necessity in bringing the
government closer to the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the Chinese government will carry out this reform
in accordance with requirements for developing a socialist market
economy and by following the principles of simplification,
uniformity and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
China will alter the functions of the government and separate
them from those of the enterprise so as to establish a highly
efficient, well-coordinated and standardized administrative
system, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Police Found Two Drug Lab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Colombian narcotics
police destroyed two cocaine laboratories near the southwest town
of Bolivar on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Police commander Colonel Gilberto Villar Jimenez said officers
burned down the labs and seized 32 kilograms of cocaine base,
3,400 kilograms of chopped leaf, 255 gallons of gasoline and 14
kilograms of lime.
</P>
<P>
Colombian police are using satellites in the search for crops
used in the production of drugs, said the colonel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
