<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Restructure Government Institutions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The country will improve the system of public servants,
building a contingent of administrators who are highly competent
and professionally specialized.
</P>
<P>
In restructuring the State Council, he said, China will focus
on reorganizing or canceling departments directly in charge of
economic management and reinforcing departments handling
macroeconomic controls and those enforcing the law and supervising
law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
This reform involves greater changes for both institutions and
people than similar previous reforms, he said. It should therefore
be handled persistently, prudently, patiently and carefully, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Government functionaries, he said, are fairly well-qualified
and most have professional expertise, so they are a very valuable
asset for China, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will adopt the methods of "channeling cadres while
allowing them to enjoy their original material benefits, providing
job-oriented training, replenishing enterprises and optimizing the
structure."
</P>
<P>
By doing so, he said, these cadres can play a full role in
industrial, commercial and banking enterprises, in law-enforcement
institutions, in cultural, educational and public health
institutions, and in other organizations.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng urged local governments at all levels to simplify their
structure and streamline their staff from top to bottom, step by
step and in an orderly way.
</P>
<P>
"We should strengthen legislation relating to administrative
institutions in order to statutorily delimit the structures,
functions, sizes and working procedures of governments at all
levels," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
