<HEADLINE> Japan to Extend 600 Million Dollars to Thai Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan will extend 600 million US
dollars to help Thai exporters fund imports of raw materials,
Thursday's Bangkok Post quoted visiting Japanese Vice Finance
Minister Eisuke Sakakibara as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 million dollars will be disbursed through the
Export-Import Bank of Japan by the end of this month, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Sakakibara, who is in charge of international affairs in the
Finance Ministry, gave a thumb-up to Thailand's progress under the
economic restructuring program of the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
When meeting Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda
Wednesday, Sakakibara said Thailand's fundamentals and long-term
prospects were strong.
</P>
<P>
About the exchange rate of baht against the dollar, he said the
only "logical direction is toward strengthening." He said that his
government supported Thailand's efforts to stabilize the currency.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese minister also said he will hold talks with
Japanese banks to continue their support for Thai borrowers.
</P>
<P>
Japanese banks hold roughly half of Thailand's private-sector
foreign debt, estimated at about 70 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sakakibara said that "borrowers and lenders both had to take
responsibility" and that the economic turmoil over the past year
had global consequences.
</P>
<P>
"This is not an 'Asian crisis' but a problem of global
capitalism," he said. 
</P>
