<HEADLINE> EU Willing to Help Re-Build Economy in Bosnian Serb Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook on Wednesday said the European Union (EU) is ready to help
resume economic development in the Serb Republic of
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The EU is willing to work with the Bosnian Serb government to
achieve reconstruction of the country's economy, Cook said when
meeting Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic and Premier Milorad
Dodik in Banja Luka, one of the largest cities in the republic.
</P>
<P>
Cook, representing the EU of which Britain is currently
president, was on a one-day visit there.
</P>
<P>
He told the two Bosnian Serb leaders that the EU has decided to
offer a total of six million ECU (6.75 million U.S. dollars) aid
package to help improve education and provide funds for police
force salaries in the country.
</P>
<P>
Before arriving in Banja Luka, Cook stopped over in Sarajevo,
where he called on former Bosnian Serb President Radovan Karadzic
to surrender to the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. tribunal indicted Karadzic for crimes against humanity
in connection with the 1992-95 siege of Sarajevo and mass
expulsions of Muslims and Croats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
