<HEADLINE> Shandong Economy Expects 11 Percent Growth for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- While economists predict an eight
percent growth for the Chinese economy this year, officials in
east China's Shandong Province are expecting the local Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) to grow by 11 percent or more in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Li Chunting, governor of Shandong who is attending the First
Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) as a deputy
to the congress, said that Shandong is capable of maintaining high
economic growth with its developed basic industries and
highly-competitive enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
Shandong scored an economic growth of 11.2 percent last year,
while the average growth for the whole country was 8.8 percent. In
1997, the total and per capita GDP for this coastal province
respectively reached 665 billion yuan (about 80 billion US
dollars) and 8,000 yuan (about 1,000 US dollars), nearly double
the 1992 figures.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Lin Shuxiang, director of the planning commission of the
Shandong provincial government, said that despite the impact of
the financial crisis in Southeast Asia, Shandong's exports are
expected to reach 15 billion US dollars this year, a 10 percent
rise over 1997.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to invest 200 billion yuan (about 24 billion
US dollars) in fixed assets in 1998, 15 percent more than in the
previous year, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also predicted that the service industry would continue to
be the province's fastest-developing sector this year, with an
expected growth rate of 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, only less than 20 percent of Shandong's urban labor
is engaged in the service sector. If this percentage can be raised
to 30, the problem of laid-off workers will be basically solved in
Shandong," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Li the governor, Shandong plans to raise its
provincial and per capita GDP to 1.03 trillion yuan and 11,400
yuan by 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
