<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures about China's Major Economic Achievements (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China has made remarkable economic
achievements over the past five years, according to a government
work report delivered by Premier Li Peng at the First Session of
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), which opened here
today.
</P>
<P>
Major figures featuring the achievements from 1993 to 1997 are:
</P>
<P>
-- In 1997, China's gross domestic product reached 7.477
trillion yuan (900.8 billion US dollars), with an annual increase
of 11 percent on average, calculated in terms of comparable
prices.
</P>
<P>
-- Last year, the economy grew by 8.8 percent, with retail
prices rising by 0.8 percent. The rural economy developed in an
all-round way, and the added value of agriculture increased by 4.5
percent annually on the average.
</P>
<P>
-- In 1997, China's total grain output reached 492.5 billion
kg, an increase of 50 billion kg over five years ago.
</P>
<P>
-- Town and township enterprises maintained a good momentum of
rapid growth. The added value of industry increased by 15.3
percent annually on average over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
-- In 1997, total steel output topped 100 million tons, more
than doubling the figure in 1985. Power-generating capacity
reached 250 million kw.
</P>
<P>
-- Transportation, post and telecommunications developed
rapidly. A total of 11,344 kilometers of railway tracks were laid
and an additional 4,083 kilometers of expressways were constructed
in the past five years. The total number of telephone lines
climbed to 110 million.
</P>
<P>
-- Investment in fixed assets over the past five years totaled
10 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
-- The volume of China's annual import and export increased
from 165.5 billion US dollars to 325.1 billion US dollars over the
last five years.
</P>
<P>
-- There was a big increase in the use of foreign funds. Actual
funds from direct foreign investment totaled 185.8 billion US
dollars over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
-- China enjoyed a favorable international balance of payments
and the national foreign exchange reserves rose from 19.4 billion
US dollars to 139.9 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- China signed or participated in 187 international treaties
over the past five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures about China's Major Economic Achievements (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- In 1997, average per capita disposable income reached 5,170
yuan for city dwellers, representing an annual increase of six
percent in real terms over the past five years. Average per capita
net income of rural residents rose to 2,090 yuan, representing an
annual increase of 5.4 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
-- Total retail sales of consumer goods increased by 10.3
percent annually in real terms.
</P>
<P>
-- Urban and rural people owned more household electrical
appliances with over 85 percent of the households having at least
one television.
</P>
<P>
-- Per capita living space rose to 8.7 square meters on average for
city dwellers and to 22 square meters for rural residents.
</P>
<P>
-- Savings deposits of urban and rural residents grew
considerably, reaching 4,628 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
-- Over the past five years, 224,000 patent applications were
approved and intellectual property rights further protected.
</P>
<P>
-- Nine-year compulsory education was basically provided in 65
percent of areas. Illiteracy among young and middle-aged
people dropped to 6 percent. Students in vocational schools
account for over 56 percent of those eligible for senior
secondary school education.
</P>
<P>
-- Over the last five years 6.87 million college students
graduated and 175,000 postgraduates completed their studies.
</P>
<P>
-- Both radio and television now reach over 85 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council submitted 66 draft laws and worked out 197
administrative statutes over the last five years, further ensuring
that the administrative functions of the government be carried
out in accordance with law.
</P>
<P>
-- Over the past five years, 35.55 million urban dwellers found
employment. A five-day work week was adopted in cities and towns.
Family planning produced remarkable results with the
population growth rate falling to 1.006 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese people became healthier, having an average life
expectancy of 70.8 years (as compared with 70 years in 1993 --
editor).
</P>
<P>
-- A unified insurance system covering workers' basic old-age
pensions was established preliminarily nation-wide, and
unemployment insurance was expanded gradually. A system to ensure
a minimum standard of living was established in over 300 cities.
</P>
<P>
-- Substantial progress was made in assisting poverty-stricken
areas and in developing poor rural areas, and basic requirements
for food and clothing for 30 million people who had lived in
absolute poverty were met.
</P>
<P>
(Note: In 1978, the impoverished population in China's rural
areas was 250 million, who accounted for one-fourth of the world's
total poverty population. The figure decreased to 65 million in
1995, or one-twentieth of the world's total. The number of people
in China living in absolute poverty at present stands at 50
million. The Chinese government has undertaken to basically meet
the need of food and clothing for the country's rural poor people
by the end of the century. -- editor) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0270 </DOCNO>
