<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Delivers Government Work Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng delivered a report
at the First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC)
which opened in the Great Hall of the People in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The report, totalling more than 17,000 Chinese characters,
summed up work of the government in the past five years and put
forward suggestions on the work of the government for 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Li said that in the past five year, China's
economy had maintained a good momentum of growth and the economic
strength of the country increased substantially.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China's gross domestic product reached 7.477
trillion yuan, with an annual increase of 11 percent on the
average, calculated in terms of comparable prices.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the economy grew by 8.8 percent, retail prices
rose by 0.8 percent. This favorable situation featuring a high
economic growth and brought inflation under effective control.
</P>
<P>
The main objectives for macro-control over the national
economy in 1998 are having an economic growth rate of eight
percent and keeping the retail price increases below three
percent, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Major breakthroughs were made in the reform aimed at
establishing a socialist market economy, a framework for the new
macro-control system was erected preliminarily and the
fundamental role of the market in the allocation of resources
was notably bolstered, he said.
</P>
<P>
China continued an all-direction, multilevel and wide-range
opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
The volume of China's annual import and export increased from
165.5 billion U.S. dollars to 325.1 billion U.S. dollars over the
past five yeas, Li said.
</P>
<P>
There was a big increase in the use of foreign funds. The
actual funds from direct foreign investment totaled 185.8
billion U.S. dollars over the past five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Delivers Government Work Report  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1997 the average per capita disposable incomes reached 5,160
yuan for city dwellers, representing an annual increase of six
percent in real terms over the past five years. The average per
capita net income of rural residents rose to 2,090 yuan,
representing an annual increase of 5.4 percent in real terms, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has returned to the motherland smoothly and
maintains its prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
The central government has given full support to the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) in its work and in the measures it has taken for dealing
with the impact of the financial crises in Southeast Asian
countries, the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's return has had a good beginning, and Hong Kong's
future will be even brighter, he added.
</P>
<P>
In his work report, Li put forward an eight-point suggestion on
the work of the government for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture will be further stabilized and strengthened. The
total grain output should be stabilized at 492.5 billion kg, and
the total cotton output at 80 million dan (four million tons).
</P>
<P>
The country should keep stable the household responsibility
contract system with remuneration linked to output, carry out
the policy of prolonging the land contract period for another 30
years, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Breakthroughs will be in the reform of state-owned enterprises.
The country will press ahead with the reform and development of
key industries and enterprises and accelerate the reorganization
and readjustment of state-owned enterprises and encourage strong
enterprises to merge with difficulty-ridden ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the total capital reserves earmarked for clearing
the bad debts of banks should be raised to 40 billion yuan, the
premier said.
</P>
<P>
China will actively and steadily carry out the reform involving
the joint share system and the joint stock cooperative system and
improve the leadership, operation and management of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to strengthen and improve macro-control.
The total investment in fixed assets this year is planned to
increase by 10 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
The country will continue to carry out an appropriately tight
financial policy and deepen the reform of its financial and
taxation systems. The income tax system should be improved and the
sales tax should be readjusted. Inheritance tax will be
introduced. China should continue its appropriately tight monetary
policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Delivers Government Work Report (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1998, Li said, China's priorities in the reform of the
financial system are to improve and strengthen the financial
control and supervision by the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
The country will do better in opening to the outside world and
continue to utilize foreign funds actively, rationally and
effectively.
</P>
<P>
"We should guide foreign investment toward agriculture,
infrastructure, basic industries, high and new technology
industries and export-oriented projects. We should encourage
foreign businessmen to further invest in the central and western
regions of China," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
It must keep to the principles of maintaining an equilibrium in
the balance of payments and keeping stable the exchange rates for
the Renminbi against other currencies.
</P>
<P>
China is to develop science, technology, education and
cultural undertakings.
</P>
<P>
"In our work in science and technology," Li said, "We should
strive to propagate the use of applicable advanced technologies
for production, distribution, consumption, environmental
protection and other fields."
</P>
<P>
"We shall basically achieve nine-year compulsory education in
areas accounting for 72 percent of the total population and
eliminate illiteracy among 3.5 million yua and middle-aged
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li pledged to improve the material and cultural conditions
for people in urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Assisting laid-off workers to find new jobs and guaranteeing
their basic needs is a pressing task for government in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"We should rely on all quarters of society to provide better
employment services and vocational training for re-employment.
We should also support laid-off workers in seeking new jobs on
their own and encourage them to become self-employed or to work
in the private sectors of the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
They should be encouraged to engage in and expand badly-needed
community services, property management and household services.
This will involve less investment and quicker results, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Delivers Government Work Report (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China should strengthen legislation relating to administrative
institutions in order to statutorily delimit the structures, sizes
and working procedures of governments at all levels.
</P>
<P>
Li called for promoting the great cause of peaceful
reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
All preparations for Macao's return are being made in an
energetic and orderly fashion, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the Taiwan authorities take into consideration
the overall interests of the Chinese nation and the fundamental
interest of the people in Taiwan, take concrete steps for the
early establishment of direct links of postal, air and shipping
services and trade between the two sides and that they respond
as early as possible to our solemn appeal that the two sides
conduct political negotiations under the principle of one
China," Li said.
</P>
<P>
On strengthening national defense and the army, the Chinese
premier said that China would complete on schedule the task of
reducing its armed forces by 500,000 persons within three years.
</P>
<P>
Referring to international situation and diplomatic work, Li
said that under the new international situation, the country
should as always uphold its independent foreign policy of peace
and open up new vistas in diplomatic work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
