<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, Italy to Promote Economic, Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi met here
Wednesday to focus on the promotion of economic and trade
relations.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso expressed his desire to strengthen economic and trade
exchanges between the two countries, mainly in investment,
privatization and welfare sectors.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said Latin American countries, especially Brazil, were
among the first countries to make investments in Italy in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The new investments would focus on energy, petroleum,
infrastructure and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The Italian prime minister arrived here Tuesday night from Sao
Paulo, the biggest city of Brazil, for his two-day visit to the
South Latin American country.
</P>
<P>
In Sao Paulo, Prodi met with Governor Mario Covas to discuss
the privatization, the public deficit and welfare reforms.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Prodi emphasized that the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur), a regional economic bloc grouping Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay, was one of the most important areas for
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is Prodi's second stop on his Latin American trip which
also includes Uruguay and Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
