<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MERCOSUR Supports Approval of U.N.-Iraq Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The member states of the Common
Market of the South (MERCOSUR), together with Bolivia and Chile,
expressed their support and congratulations for the unanimous
approval by the Security Council of the U.N.-Iraq deal.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the latin American organization, which
was established in 1991 between Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay, said they hope the peaceful solution to the weapons
inspections crisis in Iraq will bring a long-lasting and stable
peace to the gulf region.
</P>
<P>
They also spoke highly of efforts made by the United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan to negotiate the peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimous vote Monday night, the 15-member U.N. Security
Council adopted the resolution drafted by Britain and Japan that
declares "any violation (of the agreement) will have the severest
consequences for Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Under the Memorandum of Understanding signed by Annan and Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz on February 23, Iraq has agreed
to grant a U.N special group free, unconditional and unrestricted
access to its presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
The resolution adopted Monday does not spell out what the
consequences will be if Iraq violates the agreement on weapons
inspections, but U.S. officials state that any further violation
by Iraq will provide strong support for a military strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
