<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks 1.85 Billion Dollars for Bosnia, Gulf Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
asked Congress on Wednesday for extra 1.85 billion U.S. dollars to
pay for U.S. military deployments in Bosnia and the Gulf during
the current fiscal year, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
The money is part of a broader 2.49 billion U.S. dollars
supplemental request for funds during fiscal 1998, which ends on
September 30.
</P>
<P>
The request includes 1.36 billion U.S. dollars for the 36,000
U.S. troops in the Gulf who are poised to move against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, Clinton sought no money for keeping them in place into
the new fiscal year, which begins on October 1.
</P>
<P>
The request also includes 487 million U.S. dollars for the
Bosnia deployment and 642 million U.S. dollars to help cope with a
slew of recent U.S. natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton also asked the Republican-controlled
Congress for an extra 1.86 billion U.S. dollars to fund the U.S.
forces in Bosnia during fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has 8,500 troops in Bosnia. But it expects to reduce
the number to 6,900 later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Attain Eight-Percent Economic Growth Rate (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua)-- China's main objectives for
macro-control over the national economy in 1998 are having an
economic growth rate of eight percent and keeping the retail price
increases below three percent, said Premier Li Peng today.
</P>
<P>
"These objectives embody the spirit of seeking progress amidst
stability," he said at the First Session of Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC) which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
"If they are achieved, China will be able to maintain the good
momentum of development featuring high economic growth and low
inflation," he said.
</P>
<P>
China achieved 8.8 percent increase in economic growth rate in
1997 and 0.8 percent in retail price increase. The average annual
economic growth rate reached 11 percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
"Appropriately increased investment constitutes an important
condition for sustained, rapid and sound development of the
national economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He told the annual conference of the country's legislative body
that total investment in fixed assets this year is planned to
increase by 10 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
China will focus investment on agricultural, forestry and water
conservancy projects while continuing to strengthen the
construction of energy, transportation, communications,
environmental protection and other infrastructural facilities.
</P>
<P>
More input should be made in high and new technology industries
and the proportion of investment in technological upgrading should
be increased. The construction of ordinary civil housing should be
accelerated, he said.
</P>
<P>
In investing in infrastructure, he said, the Chinese government
will make sure that infrastructural facilities are rationally
distributed, tapping the potentials of existing facilities and
refraining from blindly building new ones.
</P>
<P>
The central government will support the development of
resources and major infrastructural construction in the central
and western regions of the country and stress efficiency in
utilizing this investment. We must strictly control the number of
new projects.
</P>
<P>
In principle, he said the central government will not launch
additional ordinary industrial projects, but concentrate its
strength on accelerating the construction of those projects under
construction which have good market prospects and are expected to
be economically efficient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Attain Eight-Percent Economic Growth Rate (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To promote the upgrading of their products, he said the Chinese
government will support enterprises in importing key equipment and
high and new technology equipment.
</P>
<P>
The central government will better guide enterprises to set and
adjust the direction of their investments according to market
needs through industrial policies and the publishing of relevant
information.
</P>
<P>
China will press ahead with the reform of housing, taking
effective measures to promote its commercialization and making the
construction of civil housing a new point for economic growth,
he said.
</P>
<P>
China will deepen the reform of its investment and fund-raising
systems, improving and strictly implementing the project capital
system and delineating responsibilities concerning investment and
fund-raising risks.
</P>
<P>
He went on to note that China will continue to carry out an
appropriately tight financial policy. Financial and economic
discipline should be enforced. Efforts should be made to increase
revenues and cut expenditures, keep the scale of debts under
control and further reduce deficits.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report, Li said China will strictly
control the management of taxation. The government will levy taxes
according to law and tighten tax collection and management,
resolutely fighting tax evasion, tax fraud and smuggling and
ensure that taxes owed to the government are paid so as to reduce
non-payment of taxes.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to deepen the reform of our financial and
taxation systems. The income tax system should be improved and the
sales tax should be readjusted. Inheritance tax will be
introduced, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will also improve the accounting system, tighten the
financial management of enterprises, exercise more effective
auditing and supervision and ban all kinds of arbitrary charges.
</P>
<P>
With a view to keeping expenditures below revenues, he said
China will strictly control expenditures. Relief funds for natural
disasters and re-employment and anti-poverty funds should be
increased appropriately, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
