<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sprewell Gets Suspension Reduced, Staying in Warriors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Latrell Sprewell's suspension was
reduced by an independent arbitrator on Wednesday, and the former
All-star could stay in the Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
Arbitrator John Feerick, dean of Fordham University Law School,
ruled that Sprewell would return to the Warriors on July 1, and
must be paid the 17.3 million U.S. dollars remaining on his
contract.
</P>
<P>
Sprewell, who assaulted Warriors' coach P.J. Carlesimo five
months ago, however, has to stay away from this season to have his
ban extended to 68 games and a cost of 6.4 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Warriors must offer him the remaining two years on the contract
or trade him.
</P>
<P>
Feerick's decision came 16 days after the close of a hearing on
the case Sprewell conducted in Portland, Oregon, and in New York.
</P>
<P>
Sprewell, who was a top guard in NBA, was originally banned for
one year had his contract suspended -- the longest non-drug ban in
NBA history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
