<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1:00 GMT, March 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Wednesday that any U.S. bombings of Iraq would not deter
U.N. weapons inspectors to go back to that country for searching
of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
She was answering a question at a House panel's hearing from
Sidney Yates, a Democratic representative, when the Clinton
administration would follow up any bombing campaign of Iraq once
it was seen as breaking away from its commitment to comply with an
agreement on weapons inspection, reached with U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan last week.
</P>
<P>
"I think that if (Iraq) breaks the agreement now, there will be
much greater support for our use of force than there was before,
and therefore more support in terms of pressing (Iraqi President)
Saddam Hussein to allow potentially the inspector to go back in,
even after a bombing," she said. (US-Iraq-Arms Inspection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States might consider a military
intervention in the crisis in Kosovo, an ethnic Albanian-dominated
province of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, said a senior
U.S. official Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Robert Gelbard, U.S. envoy to Bosnia, issued another strong
warning to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on troubled
Kosovo province when speaking at a meeting of the Defense Writers
Group.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard indicated Washington has not changed its long-standing
policy to respond militarily if the Balkan war in the province
breaks out.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, violence occurred in Kosovo, where Albanians make up
90 percent of its population. The Bush administration, then
Clinton's, threatened to intervene if Yugoslavia solved the crisis
through force. (US-Kosovo-Intervention)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The German parliament Wednesday gave preliminary
approval to a bill which will reverse an estimated several hundred
thousand convictions of the courts in Nazi Germany more than 50
years ago.
</P>
<P>
"It is unworthy of a state which abides by the rule of law...
when convictions still stand which were clearly based on Nazi
injustice", said Justice Minister Edzard Schmidt-Jortzig.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, which still needs the parliament's final
approval, will lift all convictions of Nazi's notorious
Volksgericht (People's Court), which was set up in Berlin to give
quick verdicts to accused traitors.
</P>
<P>
It will also quash convictions of temporary courts set up
shortly before the 1945 Nazi defeat and all other convictions
leading to the death penalty or based on 57 Nazi laws.
(Germany-Nazi Court Conviction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein Wednesday evening met
with French president's special envoy Bertrand Dufourcq to discuss
the implementation of the agreement signed by U.N. Chief Kofi
Annan and Iraq on arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq, who arrived here Tuesday evening, handed over
President Jacques Chirac's letter to Saddam during the
meeting. Saddam said he would write a letter in reply and send his
special envoy to Paris with the letter.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq, also secretary general of French Foreign Ministry,
stressed the significance his country attaches to the complete and
rapid implementation of the agreement signed late last month by
Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Iraq agrees to grant a special U.N.
inspection group free, unconditional and unrestricted access to
its presidential palaces. The group will comprise of senior
diplomats appointed by Annan and experts drawn from the
U.N. Special Commission in charge of eliminating Iraq's banned
weapons and the International Atomic Energy Agency. (Iraq-France)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
