<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's second largest company BHP's market value surged
1.58 billion US dollars Wednesday after its Chief Executive John
Prescott resigned with a payout package estimated at 13 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Federal Treasurer Peter Costello resisted calls
for big-spending federal budget for the coming fiscal year
Wednesday despite the Asian crisis taking its toll on Australia's
exports and reducing the prospect of job growth.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- The resignation of BHP's Chief Executive John Prescott opens
up possibility that a non-Australian will take the reins of the
largest resources company in Australia, which despite a savaging
of its share prices is still a 21 billion US dollar colossus.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian economy is losing momentum even before the
full force of the Asian crisis hits home, with new figures
revealing that economic growth slowed in the last three months of
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
