<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Voids Miami Mayoral Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A Miami-Dade County circuit
court judge in Florida Wednesday ruled last November's Miami
mayoral election is void and ordered a new election be held in 60
days.
</P>
<P>
Judge Thomas Wilson said there was sufficient evidence of
tampering with absentee ballots to taint the election of Xavier
Suarez, who defeated incumbent mayor Joe Carollo, news reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The new election will cost the city between 100,000 and 125,000
dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, in his ruling, Wilson made it clear he felt Suarez did
not know of the vote tampering.
</P>
<P>
Miami's city charter calls for the city commission to appoint
an interim mayor.
</P>
<P>
Carollo had hoped Wilson would throw out the absentee ballots
and declare him the winner.
</P>
<P>
Two investigations of the election are still in progress by the
Florida Department of Law Enforcement and the Miami-Dade State
Attorney's Office.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
