<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloning Not Likely to Help Infertile Couples: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Leading fertility experts said
Wednesday that cloning is unlikely to work as a helping technique
for infertile couples in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there is any role for cloning for at least five
years, until many more animal studies have been done and we
understand exactly what is involved," said professor Robert
Edwards, who helped to produce the first test tube baby in the
world.
</P>
<P>
He told a symposium that the use of cloning in humans may be to
understand human system better, not to clone people.
</P>
<P>
Other experts attending the symposium, which is to mark the
20th anniversary of the birth of the world's first IVF (in vitro
fertilization) babies, agreed with professor Edwards.
</P>
<P>
Professor Robert Winston, a British fertility expert, said that
he also doesn't think there are any implications for human
fertility of any significance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
