<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: Inspections Continue Even After Bombing Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Wednesday that any U.S. bombings of Iraq would not
deter U.N. weapons inspectors to go back to that country for
searching of weapons of mass destructions.
</P>
<P>
She was answering a question at a House panel's hearing from
Sidney Yates, a Democratic representative, when the Clinton
administration would follow up any bombing campaign of Iraq once
it was seen as breaking away from its commitment to comply with an
agreement on weapons inspections, reached with U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan last week.
</P>
<P>
"I think that if (Iraq) breaks the agreement now, there will be
much greater support for our use of force than there was before,
and therefore more support in terms of pressing (Iraqi President)
Saddam Hussein to allow potentially the inspector to go back in,
even after a bombing," she said.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts have said bombing may result in Iraq barring U.N.
inspectors for good. This is also an issue that critics of the
U.S. Iraq policy have repeatedly raised.
</P>
<P>
Sonny Callanhan, a Republican representative and the chairman
of the House of Representative Appropriations Subcommittee, said
some members of Congress were "grossly disappointed" that
"countries that have been huge recipients of American aid in the
past" had not readily backed the U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to several Arab countries that were ambiguous
about using military force against Iraq when Albright and Defense
Secretary William Cohen talked with the leaders of these
countries.
</P>
<P>
But Albright said she was "comfortable" with the level of Arab
support for the U.S. policy on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I have to tell you that both Secretary Cohen and I feel
comfortable with the support that we are getting from them,"she
said.
</P>
<P>
"We actually got what we considered good statements of
support," she said. But "they are in the neighborhood with the
bully... and therefore their statements to some extent are
tailored to that regard," she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright dismissed suggestions that diplomats accompanying
weapons inspectors of the U.N. Special Commission on visits to
sensitive sites might tip off Iraq in advance on when searches
were coming.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a system whereby the diplomats will not be in a
position to warn anyone," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
