<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students in UK Walk Out in Protest on Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of students
across Britain boycotted the class Wednesday to protest against
the government's plans to charge 1,000 pound-a-year tuition fees.
</P>
<P>
The National Union of Students said the students picketed
college entrances, distributed leaflets in towns and released
thousands of anti-tuition fee balloons.
</P>
<P>
Until the coming September, the higher education in Britain is
free.
</P>
<P>
Students' response to its call for a walk-out at more than 150
colleges and universities across the country had far exceeded
expectations, the students union said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Government ministers explain the fees are necessary to fund
further expansion of higher education, and only one-third will
actually have to pay the full amount because the fees are means
tested.
</P>
<P>
But the union believes the charges will discourage people from
going to university and applications to universities for this
September has dropped.
</P>
<P>
"Fees are killing access to higher education. It is time for
the government to give up on the legislation and rethink the
financial arrangements for students and for British higher
education," said Douglas Trainer, general secretary of the
National Union of Students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
