<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Expansion Pushed by U.S. Weapon Makers: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. weapons makers are playing
a leading role in lobbying for the expansion of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), the World Policy Institute said in a
report issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
NATO last July decided to accept Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic in 1999. The U.S. government said that it will make
America safer, NATO stronger and Europe more stable.
</P>
<P>
The institute said weapons manufacturing companies such as
Lockheed-Martin Corp. and Boeing Co. are major supporters of the
expansion.
</P>
<P>
These companies are eyeing possibly billions in sales of
warplanes to Central European nations, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The big prize in selling to new NATO members will be aircraft.
Poland could buy more than 100 F-16 fighters, built by Lockheed
Martin in Forth Worth, Texas. Boeing is hoping the Czech Republic
will buy a few dozen F-18 fighters, built in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
These and other defense contractors are also hoping to sell
radar and communications systems. Bell Helicopter Textron Inc.,
also of Forth Worth, hopes to sell helicopters to Romania, a
country that hopes to join NATO in later expansion rounds.
</P>
<P>
With lucrative business at stake, these companies have become
actively involved in the NATO expansion lobbying effort, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Boeing is a corporate financer of the American Friends of the
Czech Republic. The U.S. Committee to Expand NATO is headed by a
Lockheed Martin vice president.
</P>
<P>
A Lockheed Martin executive, Bernard Schwartz, donated 50,000
U.S. dollars to the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee last
summer shortly after he appeared at the U.S. Committee to Expand
NATO dinner briefing for a dozen members of the Senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
