<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Considers Military Intervention in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States might
consider a military intervention in the crisis in Kosovo, an
ethnic Albanian-dominated province of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia, said a senior U.S. official Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Robert Gelbard, U.S. envoy to Bosnia, issued another strong
warning to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on troubled
Kosovo province when speaking at a meeting of the Defense Writers
Group.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard indicated Washington has not changed its long-standing
policy to respond militarily if the Balkan war in the province
breaks out.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. policy has not changed. We're prepared to try to find new
and other tools to make this effective. But the key is we're going
to have effective means to deal with these problems, and we have
warned Milosevic appropriately," Gelbard said.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, violence occurred in Kosovo, where Albanians make up
90 percent of its population. The Bush administration, then
Clinton's, threatened to intervene if Yugoslavia solved the crisis
through force.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to be prepared to deal with this problem... using
every appropriate tool we have at our command," Gelbard said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will attend an urgent
meeting on Kosovo next Monday in London with foreign ministers
from Germany, Britain, France, Russia and Italy, according to
the envoy.
</P>
<P>
The economy in Yugoslavia is "dismal," and "the situation could
become an awful lot worse and we can make it worse," if Belgrade
uses force in Kosovo, Gelbard said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the reduction of U.S. troops in Bosnia, Gelbard
said he expects a slight reduction, mostly in logistical support,
from about 8,000 troops to about 7,000. Three maneuver battalions
will be maintained in the contingent.
</P>
<P>
The United States, through NATO, will try to get other
countries, particularly Western European nations, to take on some
responsibilities in support tasks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard said the Bosnia mission will become more localized,
focusing on potential civil disturbances that could arise from the
return of refugees and displaced people, installing elected
municipal governments and economic reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
