<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Responds to IMF Criticism of Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian government Wednesday
said it had been implementing austerity measures for some time to
counter the IMF (International Monetary Fund) criticism of its
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF urged more progress on structural reforms by Belgium,
particularly to combat a growing jobless rate, in its annual
review of the Belgian economy Tuesday. It also asked Belgium to
lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said it remained concerned about "the continuing
serious structural problems in the economy, in particular the high
level of unemployment and the high, albeit declining ratio of
public debt to Gross Domestic Product."
</P>
<P>
Belgian Budget Minister Herman Van Rompuy responded by saying
that Belgium had made good progress in cutting its debt/GDP ratio
though it was still double the 60 percent target laid down for
participation in Europe's single currency.
</P>
<P>
The state debt of Belgium, which was 135 percent in 1993, had
been "drastically" reduced due to the efforts of the government,
according to the budget minister.
</P>
<P>
He said Belgium was going towards 118 percent for 1998 but
admitted that the country would have to maintain a strict budget
policy in coming years.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said Belgium should aim, over the medium term, to
reduce the tax burden, involving reforms in the health care and
pension systems.
</P>
<P>
Spending ceilings were needed for each level of government "to
create scope for significant cut in the tax burden on labor
income, which should reduce labor costs," said the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Van Rompuy said the Belgian government had already planned to
reduce employers' social charges -- "charges that weigh on
employment of people, hiring people."
</P>
<P>
Responding to IMF remarks that the tax burden on labor income
should be cut, he said the Belgian government was planning to
reintroduce the full indexation of tax scales from January 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the jobless rate in Flanders region,
the northern half of Belgium, was among the lowest in western
Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
