<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Debates Future Status of Puerto Rico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives Wednesday debated whether to allow Puerto Rico
vote to be the 51st U.S. state, remain a U.S. territory or an
independent nation.
</P>
<P>
The House is expected to vote later Wednesday on the bill
sponsored by Alaska Republican Don Young, which called for a
plebiscite on the territory by the end of the year to decide its
future status.
</P>
<P>
The former Spanish colony became a U.S. possession after the
1898 Spanish-American War.
</P>
<P>
As a commonwealth, Puerto Ricans, represented in the U.S.
Congress by a delegate without voting right, are U.S. citizens but
cannot vote in U.S. elections.
</P>
<P>
"This is a bill that establishes the right of Puerto Rico to
self-determination for the first time in 100 years," said Young.
</P>
<P>
"The 3.8 million citizens in Puerto Rico have waited an entire
century for the United States to provide them with this
opportunity," Young told a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The passage of the bill was threatened by conservative
Republicans who insisted English should be the Spanish-speaking
island's only official language if it gains U.S. statehood.
</P>
<P>
An amendment sponsored by New York Republican Gerald Solomon
proposed making English the only official language in Puerto Rico
if it becomes a state. The amendment would also require Puerto
Rican public schools to teach in English.
</P>
<P>
"Admitting a state requires the assimilation of a territory
within the union of states and language differences are the number
one barrier to actual assimilation," Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of the bill said the English-only requirement was a
"poisoned" amendment that had no place in the discussion. They
said that Hawaii and New Mexico have two official languages.
</P>
<P>
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt called the amendment a
"slap in the face" to the Puerto Rican people who deserved the
opportunity to decide their political future. "It is a simple
issue of basic human rights," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn to Reverse Nazi Court Convictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament Wednesday gave
preliminary approval to a bill which will reverse an estimated
several hundred thousand convictions of the courts in Nazi Germany
more than 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"It is unworthy of a state which abides by the rule of law...
when convictions still stand which were clearly based on Nazi
injustice," said Justice Minister Edzard Schmidt-Jortzig.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, which still needs the parliament's final
approval, will lift all convictions of Nazi's notorious
Volksgericht (People's Court), which was set up in Berlin to give
quick verdicts to accused traitors.
</P>
<P>
It will also quash convictions of temporary courts set up
shortly before the 1945 Nazi defeat and all other convictions
leading to the death penalty or based on 57 Nazi laws.
</P>
<P>
However, the bill will not apply to the conviction of soldiers
sentenced to death under military law as the military practice
existed before the Nazis took power in 1933. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
