<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Reaffirms Coordination With Lebanon On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouq al-Sharaa Wednesday stressed that his country will
coordinate with Lebanon on the Israeli proposal to withdraw from
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference with his Lebanese
counterpart Farez Boueiz, al-Sharaa said that the Israeli proposal
deformed the United Nations resolution 425, which calls on Israel
to end its occupation of south Lebanon without conditions.
</P>
<P>
It aims to drag Lebanon into an unknown condition, he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel had said it is willing to implement the United Nations
Resolution 425 provided the Lebanese government agrees Israeli security
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
After the proposal was rejected by both Lebanon and Syria on
grounds that Israel attached preconditions for the resolution,
the Israeli government is seeking France's help for a mediation
mission in view of Paris's close ties with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa said that France will never carry out this task if it
does not gain the approval from Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
He added that he had discussed with Boueiz about the role
France will play on the issue, stressing that France should play
an efficient role in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon with some 40,000
troops deployed on Lebanese soil as peacekeepers. The two
countries have vowed to hold negotiations with Israel
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian minister arrived here Wednesday night. He will also
hold talks with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi, Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri and House Speaker Nabih Berri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn to Reverse Nazi Court Convictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament Wednesday gave
preliminary approval to a bill which will reverse an estimated
several hundred thousand convictions of the courts in Nazi Germany
more than 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"It is unworthy of a state which abides by the rule of law...
when convictions still stand which were clearly based on Nazi
injustice", said Justice Minister Edzard Schmidt-Jortzig.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, which still needs the parliament's final
approval, will lift all convictions of Nazi's notorious
Volksgericht (People's Court), which was set up in Berlin to give
quick verdicts to accused traitors.
</P>
<P>
It will also quash convictions of temporary courts set up
shortly before the 1945 Nazi defeat and all other convictions
leading to the death penalty or based on 57 Nazi laws.
</P>
<P>
It is noted that the bill will not apply to the conviction of
soldiers sentenced to death under military law when the death
penalty was decided before the Nazi takeover in 1933.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980305.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Proposes Strategy to Improve Ties With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive arm, Wednesday proposed a strategy
for deepening Turkey's ties with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The Commission Wednesday made the proposal in a bid to improve
its badly soured relations with Turkey over Ankara's frustrated
efforts to be accepted as a candidate for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
It urged the EU members to release a fund of some 375 million
ECUs (around 400 million U.S. dollars) to finance the strategy,
which includes a broader customs union and cooperation in
industry, services and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"The European strategy which we proposed for Turkey will lead
to a deepening of our relations. This will be to the benefit of
all our citizens," EU Foreign Affairs Commissioner Hans van den
Broek said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that Turkey's democratic institutions and human
rights records must be improved in order to prepare itself for the
eventual EU membership.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have made clear what we expect from Turkey and what
we have to offer for Turkey," said the commissioner, who also said
that Ankara was now not interested in political dialogue with the
EU.
</P>
<P>
In a second report to the European Parliament, the Commission
said the Turkish government's program for improving the human
rights situation and democratization "has not yet had sufficient
impact on the situation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
